# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: set-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In mathematics, the **axiom of choice**, abbreviated **AC** or **AoC**, is an axiom of set theory.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Informally put, the axiom of choice says that given any collection of non-empty sets, one can identify another set containing one element chosen from each set, even if the collection is infinite.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Formally, the axiom establishes existence rather than a construction; it states that for every set I and every I -indexed family $(S_{i})_{i\in I}$ of nonempty sets, there exists an I -indexed set $(x_{i})_{i\in I}$ of elements of $\cup _{i\in I}S_{i}$ such that $x_{i}\in S_{i}$ for every $i\in I$ .
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice was formulated in 1904 by Ernst Zermelo in order to formalize his proof of the well-ordering theorem.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] An illustrative example is sets picked from the natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] From such sets, one may always select the smallest number, e.g. given the sets {{4, 5, 6}, {10, 12}, {1, 400, 617, 8000}}, the set containing each smallest element is {4, 10, 1}.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In this case, "select the smallest number" is a choice function.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Even if infinitely many sets are collected from the natural numbers, it will always be possible to form a choice function from choosing the smallest element from each set to produce a set; the axiom of choice is not needed here.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] On the other hand, for the collection of all non-empty subsets of the real numbers, there is *no* known *canonical* rule by which one can choose one element from each of these subsets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In that case, the axiom of choice must be invoked to construct the desired choice function.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Bertrand Russell coined an analogy: for any (even infinite) collection of unordered pairs of shoes, one can pick out the left shoe from each pair to obtain an appropriate collection (i.e. set) of shoes; this makes it possible to define a choice function without using the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Although originally controversial, the axiom of choice is now used without reservation by most mathematicians, and is included in the standard form of axiomatic set theory, Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice (ZFC).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One motivation for this is that a number of generally accepted mathematical results, such as Tychonoff's theorem, require the axiom of choice for their proofs.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Contemporary set theorists also study axioms that are not compatible with the axiom of choice, such as the axiom of determinacy.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] While some varieties of constructive mathematics avoid the axiom of choice, others embrace it.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A choice function (also called selector or selection) is a function f , defined on a collection X of nonempty sets, such that for every set A in X , $f(A)$ is an element of A .
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Each choice function on a family X of nonempty sets is an element of the Cartesian product of the sets in X , and vice versa.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The Cartesian product of any collection of nonempty sets is nonempty.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This form implies a more general form where the Cartesian product is of a general indexed family of sets (which may contain duplicates), since one can always select the same element from duplicate factors.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are many other equivalent statements of the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These are equivalent in the sense that, in the presence of other basic axioms of set theory, they imply the axiom of choice and are implied by it.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Note that $P\lor Q\lor R$ is logically equivalent to $(\lnot P\land \lnot Q)\implies R$ .
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This guarantees for any partition of a set X the existence of a subset C of X containing exactly one element from each part of the partition.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] (with the empty set removed) has a choice function.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Authors who use this formulation often speak of the *choice function on A*, but this is a slightly different notion of choice function.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Its domain is the power set of A (with the empty set removed), and so makes sense for any set A , whereas with the definition used elsewhere in this article, the domain of a choice function on a *collection of sets* is that collection, and so only makes sense for sets of sets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Until the late 19th century, the axiom of choice was often used implicitly, although it had not yet been formally stated.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, after having established that the set *X* contains only non-empty sets, a mathematician might have said "let *F*(*s*) be one of the members of *s* for all *s* in *X*" to define a function *F*.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In general, it is impossible to prove that *F* exists without the axiom of choice, but this seems to have gone unnoticed until Zermelo.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The existence of a choice function for a finite collection of nonempty sets can be proved by the principle of finite induction, without appealing to the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The proof uses the fact that, given a *single* nonempty set ⁠ A ⁠, first-order logic allows choosing some concrete ⁠ $a\in A$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] However, since a proof in first-order logic must be finite, one cannot make an infinite number of choices with first-order logic alone.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Another case where the axiom of choice is not needed is when there exists an explicit rule that gives a *canonical* choice function.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, if each member of the collection ⁠ X ⁠ is a nonempty subset of the natural numbers, then one such explicit rule is to choose the *smallest element* of each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The canonical choice function that maps each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠ to its smallest element can again be constructed in ZF without the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In general, if the union of all sets in ⁠ X ⁠ can be well-ordered, then a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠ can be constructed without using the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Note that it does not suffice that each ⁠ $A\in X$ ⁠ can be well-ordered, since the axiom of choice may be needed to choose a *canonical well-ordering* for each ⁠ A ⁠ anyway.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As an example where the axiom of choice is required, let ⁠ X ⁠ be set of all non-empty subsets of the real numbers.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Choosing the least element from each set no longer works, because some subsets of the real numbers do not have least elements.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, the open interval ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠ does not have a least element: if ⁠ x ⁠ is in ⁠ $(0,1)$ ⁠, then so is ⁠ $x/2$ ⁠, and ⁠ $x/2$ ⁠ is always strictly smaller than ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This strategy fails here because the natural order of real numbers is not a well-order.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If there exists a different ordering of the real numbers which is a well-ordering, then applying the least-element strategy with respect to that ordering would give a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Conversely, if there exists a choice function for ⁠ X ⁠, then the proof of the well-ordering theorem would show that a well-ordering of the real numbers does exist.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Let ⁠ S ⁠ be the unit circle, and ⁠ G ⁠ be the group consisting of all rational rotations (i.e., rotations by angles which are rational multiples of ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Since ⁠ G ⁠ is countable while ⁠ S ⁠ is uncountable, ⁠ S ⁠ must break up into uncountably many orbits under the action of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Using the axiom of choice, we could pick a single point from each orbit, obtaining an uncountable subset ⁠ X ⁠ of ⁠ S ⁠ with the property that all of its translates by ⁠ G ⁠ are disjoint from ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The set of those translates partitions the circle into a countable collection of pairwise disjoint sets, which are all pairwise congruent.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The set ⁠ X ⁠ will be non-measurable for any rotation-invariant countably additive measure on ⁠ S ⁠: if ⁠ X ⁠ has zero measure, countable additivity would imply that the whole circle has zero measure.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If ⁠ X ⁠ has positive measure, countable additivity would show that the circle has infinite measure.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Applying a similar construction to the three-dimensional ball can result in a set that is non-measurable even for any rotation-invariant *finitely* additive measure, as shown by the Banach–Tarski paradox.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A proof requiring the axiom of choice may establish the existence of an object without *canonically* defining the object in the language of set theory.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, while the axiom of choice implies that there is a well-ordering of the real numbers, there are models of set theory with the axiom of choice in which no individual well-ordering of the reals is definable.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Similarly, although a subset of the real numbers that is not Lebesgue measurable can be proved to exist using the axiom of choice, it is consistent that no such set is definable.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice asserts the existence of these intangibles (objects that are proved to exist, but which cannot be constructed in any *canonical* way), which may conflict with some philosophical principles.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Because there is no canonical well-ordering of all sets, a construction that relies on a well-ordering may not produce a canonical result, even if a canonical result is desired (as is often the case in category theory).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This has been used as an argument against the use of the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Another argument against the axiom of choice is that it implies the existence of objects that may seem counterintuitive.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One example is the Banach–Tarski paradox, which says that it is possible to decompose the 3-dimensional solid unit ball into finitely many pieces and, using only rotations and translations, reassemble the pieces into two solid balls each with the same volume as the original.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The pieces in this decomposition, constructed using the axiom of choice, are non-measurable sets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Despite these seemingly paradoxical results, most mathematicians accept the axiom of choice as a valid principle for proving new results in mathematics.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Theorems of ZF hold true in any model of that theory, regardless of the truth or falsity of the axiom of choice in that particular model.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The implications of choice below, including weaker versions of the axiom itself, are listed because they are not theorems of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The Banach–Tarski paradox, for example, is neither provable nor disprovable from ZF alone: it is impossible to construct the required decomposition of the unit ball in ZF, but also impossible to prove there is no such decomposition.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Such statements can be rephrased as conditional statements—for example, "If AC holds, then the decomposition in the Banach–Tarski paradox exists." Such conditional statements are provable in ZF when the original statements are provable from ZF and the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As discussed above, in the classical theory of ZFC, the axiom of choice enables nonconstructive proofs in which the existence of a type of object is proved without an explicit canonical construction of an instance of this type.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In fact, in set theory and topos theory, Diaconescu's theorem shows that the axiom of choice implies the law of excluded middle.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The principle is thus not available in constructive set theory, where non-classical logic is employed.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The situation is different when the principle is formulated in Martin-Löf type theory.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There and higher-order Heyting arithmetic, the appropriate statement of the axiom of choice is (depending on approach) included as an axiom or provable as a theorem.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A cause for this difference is that the axiom of choice in type theory does not have the extensionality properties that the axiom of choice in constructive set theory does.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The type theoretical context is discussed further below.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Different choice principles have been thoroughly studied in the constructive contexts and the principles' status varies between different school and varieties of the constructive mathematics.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Some results in constructive set theory use the axiom of countable choice or the axiom of dependent choice, which do not imply the law of the excluded middle.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Although the axiom of countable choice in particular is commonly used in constructive mathematics, its use has also been questioned.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It has been known since as early as 1922 that the axiom of choice may fail in a variant of ZF with urelements, through the technique of permutation models introduced by Abraham Fraenkel and developed further by Andrzej Mostowski.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The basic technique can be illustrated as follows: Let *x**n* and *y**n* be distinct urelements for *n*=1, 2, 3..., and build a model where each set is symmetric under the interchange *x**n* ↔ *y**n* for all but a finite number of *n*.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1938, Kurt Gödel showed that the *negation* of the axiom of choice is not a theorem of ZF by constructing an inner model (the constructible universe) that satisfies ZFC, thus showing that ZFC is consistent if ZF itself is consistent.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1963, Paul Cohen employed the technique of forcing, developed for this purpose, to show that, assuming ZF is consistent, the axiom of choice itself is not a theorem of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] He did this by constructing a much more complex model that satisfies ZF¬C (ZF with the negation of AC added as axiom) and thus showing that ZF¬C is consistent.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Cohen's model is a symmetric model, which is similar to permutation models, but uses "generic" subsets of the natural numbers (justified by forcing) in place of urelements.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Together these results establish that the axiom of choice is logically independent of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The assumption that ZF is consistent is harmless because adding another axiom to an already inconsistent system cannot make the situation worse.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Because of independence, the decision whether to use the axiom of choice (or its negation) in a proof cannot be made by appeal to other axioms of set theory.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One argument in favor of using the axiom of choice is that it is convenient because it allows one to prove some simplifying propositions that otherwise could not be proved.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Frequently, the axiom of choice allows generalizing a theorem to "larger" objects.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, it is provable without the axiom of choice that every vector space of finite dimension has a basis, but the generalization to all vector spaces requires the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Likewise, a finite product of compact spaces can be proven to be compact without the axiom of choice, but the generalization to infinite products (Tychonoff's theorem) requires the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The proof of the independence result also shows that a wide class of mathematical statements, including all statements that can be phrased in the language of Peano arithmetic, are provable in ZF if and only if they are provable in ZFC.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Statements in this class include the statement that P = NP, the Riemann hypothesis, and many other unsolved mathematical problems.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] When attempting to solve problems in this class, it makes no difference whether ZF or ZFC is employed if the only question is the existence of a proof.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It is possible, however, that there is a shorter proof of a theorem from ZFC than from ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of choice is not the only significant statement that is independent of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, the generalized continuum hypothesis (GCH) is not only independent of ZF, but also independent of ZFC.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] However, ZF plus GCH implies AC, making GCH a strictly stronger claim than AC, even though they are both independent of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of constructibility and the generalized continuum hypothesis each imply the axiom of choice and are strictly stronger than it.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In class theories such as Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory and Morse–Kelley set theory, there is an axiom called the axiom of global choice that is stronger than the axiom of choice for sets because it also applies to proper classes.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The axiom of global choice follows from the axiom of limitation of size.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Tarski's axiom, which is used in Tarski–Grothendieck set theory and states (in the vernacular) that every set belongs to *some* Grothendieck universe, is stronger than the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are important statements that, assuming the axioms of ZF but neither AC nor ¬AC, are equivalent to the axiom of choice (that is, their truth values in ZF, while undecidable, are the same as that of AC).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The most important among them are Zorn's lemma and the well-ordering theorem.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In fact, Zermelo initially introduced the axiom of choice in order to formalize his proof of the well-ordering theorem.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Several results in category theory invoke the axiom of choice for their proof.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These results might be weaker than, equivalent to, or stronger than the axiom of choice, depending on the strength of the technical foundations.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, if one defines categories in terms of sets, that is, as sets of objects and morphisms (usually called a small category), then there is no category of all sets, and so it is difficult for a category-theoretic formulation to apply to all sets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] On the other hand, other foundational descriptions of category theory are considerably stronger, and an identical category-theoretic statement of choice may be stronger than the standard formulation, à la class theory, mentioned above.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are several weaker statements unprovable in ZF that are logically implied by the axiom of choice (AC) within ZF but are not equivalent to AC.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One example is the axiom of dependent choice (DC).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] A still weaker example is the axiom of countable choice (ACω or CC), which states that a choice function exists for any countable family of nonempty sets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] These axioms are sufficient for many proofs in elementary mathematical analysis, and are consistent with some principles, such as the Lebesgue measurability of all subsets of real numbers, that are disprovable from the full axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Given an ordinal parameter α ≥ ω+2 – for every set *S* with rank less than α, *S* is well-orderable.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Given an ordinal parameter α ≥ 1 – for every set *S* with Hartogs number less than ωα, *S* is well-orderable.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As the ordinal parameter is increased, these approximate the full axiom of choice more and more closely.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Other choice axioms weaker than axiom of choice include the Boolean prime ideal theorem and the axiom of uniformization.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The former is equivalent in ZF to Tarski's 1930 ultrafilter lemma: every filter is a subset of some ultrafilter.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] One of the most interesting aspects of the axiom of choice is the large number of places in mathematics where it shows up.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Here are some statements that require the axiom of choice in the sense that they are not provable from ZF but are provable from ZFC (ZF plus AC).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Equivalently, these statements are true in all models of ZFC but false in some models of ZF.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Does the partition principle imply the axiom of choice?
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are several historically important set-theoretic statements implied by AC whose equivalence to AC is open.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Zermelo cited the partition principle, which was formulated before AC itself, as a justification for believing AC.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In 1906, Russell declared PP to be equivalent, but whether the partition principle implies AC is an old open problem in set theory, and the equivalences of the other statements are similarly hard old open problems.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In every *known* model of ZF where choice fails, these statements fail too, but it is unknown whether they can hold without choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] If we abbreviate by BP the claim that every set of real numbers has the property of Baire, then BP is stronger than ¬AC, which asserts the nonexistence of any choice function on perhaps only a single set of nonempty sets.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Strengthened negations may be compatible with weakened forms of AC.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For example, ZF + DC + BP is consistent, if ZF is.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] It is also consistent with ZF + DC that every set of reals is Lebesgue measurable, but this consistency result, due to Robert M.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Solovay, cannot be proved in ZFC itself, but requires a mild large cardinal assumption (the existence of an inaccessible cardinal).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] The much stronger axiom of determinacy, or AD, implies that every set of reals is Lebesgue measurable, has the property of Baire, and has the perfect set property (all three of these results are refuted by AC itself).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] ZF + DC + AD is consistent provided that a sufficiently strong large cardinal axiom is consistent (the existence of infinitely many Woodin cardinals).
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Quine's system of axiomatic set theory, New Foundations (NF), takes its name from the title ("New Foundations for Mathematical Logic") of the 1937 article that introduced it.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In the NF axiomatic system, the axiom of choice can be disproved.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] There are models of Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory in which the axiom of choice is false.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] We shall abbreviate "Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory plus the negation of the axiom of choice" by ZF¬C.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] For certain models of ZF¬C, it is possible to validate the negation of some standard ZFC theorems.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] As any model of ZF¬C is also a model of ZF, it is the case that for each of the following statements, there exists a model of ZF in which that statement is true.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Additionally, by imposing definability conditions on sets (in the sense of descriptive set theory) one can often prove restricted versions of the axiom of choice from axioms incompatible with general choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This appears, for example, in the Moschovakis coding lemma.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] In type theory, a different kind of statement is known as the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] This form begins with two types, σ and τ, and a relation *R* between objects of type σ and objects of type τ.
[src:set-theory/axiom-of-choice] Unlike in set theory, the axiom of choice in type theory is typically stated as an axiom scheme, in which *R* varies over all formulas or over all formulas of a particular logical form.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] In mathematical set theory, **Cantor's theorem** is a fundamental result which states that, for any set A , the set of all subsets of $A,$ known as the power set of $A,$ has a strictly greater cardinality than A itself.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For finite sets, Cantor's theorem can be seen to be true by simple enumeration of the number of subsets.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Counting the empty set as a subset, a set with n elements has a total of $2^{n}$ subsets, and the theorem holds because $2^{n}>n$ for all non-negative integers.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Much more significant is Cantor's discovery of an argument that is applicable to any set, and shows that the theorem holds for infinite sets also.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] As a consequence, the cardinality of the real numbers, which is the same as that of the power set of the integers, is strictly larger than the cardinality of the integers; see Cardinality of the continuum for details.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The theorem is named for Georg Cantor, who first stated and proved it at the end of the 19th century.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Cantor's theorem had immediate and important consequences for the philosophy of mathematics.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For instance, by iteratively taking the power set of an infinite set and applying Cantor's theorem, we obtain an endless hierarchy of infinite cardinals, each strictly larger than the one before it.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Consequently, the theorem implies that there is no largest cardinal number (colloquially, "there's no largest infinity").
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Cantor's argument is elegant and remarkably simple.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The complete proof is presented below, with detailed explanations to follow.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The set $B=\{x\in A\mid x\notin f(x)\}$ exists via the axiom schema of specification, and $B\in {\mathcal {P}}(A)$ because $B\subseteq A$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Suppose towards a contradiction that f is surjective.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Then there exists a $\xi \in A$ such that $f(\xi )=B$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] By the definition of B , we have $\xi \in B$ if and only if $\xi \notin f(\xi )=B$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Having derived a contradiction by assuming an arbitrary map f is surjective, we conclude that no map from A to ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ is surjective.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] However, there exist injections from A to ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ , for instance $g:x\mapsto \{x\}$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] By definition of cardinality, we have $\operatorname {card} (X)<\operatorname {card} (Y)$ for any two sets X and Y if and only if there is an injective function but no bijective function from X to Y .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] It suffices to show that there is no surjection from X to Y .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] This is the heart of Cantor's theorem: there is no surjective function from any set A to its power set.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] To establish this, it is enough to show that no function f (that maps elements in A to subsets of A ) can reach every possible subset, i.e., we just need to demonstrate the existence of a subset of A that is not equal to $f(x)$ for any $x\in A$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] This means, by definition, that for all $x\in A$ , $x\in B$ if and only if $x\notin f(x)$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For all x the sets B and $f(x)$ cannot be equal because B was constructed from elements of A whose images under f did not include themselves.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For all $x\in A$ either $x\in f(x)$ or $x\notin f(x)$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] If $x\in f(x)$ then $f(x)$ cannot equal B because $x\in f(x)$ by assumption and $x\notin B$ by definition.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] If $x\notin f(x)$ then $f(x)$ cannot equal B because $x\notin f(x)$ by assumption and $x\in B$ by the definition of B .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Therefore, by reductio ad absurdum, the assumption must be false.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Thus there is no $\xi \in A$ such that $f(\xi )=B$ ; in other words, B is not in the image of f and f does not map onto every element of the power set of A , i.e., f is not surjective.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Finally, to complete the proof, we need to exhibit an injective function from A to its power set.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Finding such a function is trivial: just map x to the singleton set $\{x\}$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The argument is now complete, and we have established the strict inequality for any set A that $\operatorname {card} (A)<\operatorname {card} ({\mathcal {P}}(A))$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Another way to think of the proof is that B , empty or non-empty, is always in the power set of A .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For f to be onto, some element of A must map to B .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] But that leads to a contradiction: no element of B can map to B because that would contradict the criterion of membership in B , thus the element mapping to B must not be an element of B meaning that it satisfies the criterion for membership in B , another contradiction.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] So the assumption that an element of A maps to B must be false; and f cannot be onto.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Because of the double occurrence of x in the expression " $x\in f(x)$ ", this is a diagonal argument.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] 2. each column of the table is labelled by a unique y from the power set of A ; the columns are ordered by the argument to f , i.e. the column labels are $f(x_{1}),f(x_{2})$ , ..., in this order.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] 3. the intersection of each row x and column y records a true/false bit whether $x\in y$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Given the order chosen for the row and column labels, the main diagonal D of this table thus records whether $x\in f(x)$ for each $x\in A$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Each row records the values of the indicator function of the set corresponding to the column.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The indicator function of B coincides with the logically negated (swap "true" and "false") entries of the main diagonal.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Thus the indicator function of B does not agree with any column in at least one entry.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Despite the simplicity of the above proof, it is rather difficult for an automated theorem prover to produce it.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The main difficulty lies in an automated discovery of the Cantor diagonal set.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Lawrence Paulson noted in 1992 that Otter could not do it, whereas Isabelle could, albeit with a certain amount of direction in terms of tactics that might perhaps be considered cheating.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Let us examine the proof for the specific case when A is countably infinite.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Without loss of generality, we may take $A=\mathbb {N} =\{1,2,3,\ldots \}$ , the set of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Suppose that $\mathbb {N}$ is equinumerous with its power set ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Indeed, ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ contains infinite subsets of $\mathbb {N}$ , e.g. the set of all positive even numbers $\{2,4,6,\ldots \}=\{2k:k\in \mathbb {N} \}$ , along with the empty set $\varnothing$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Now that we have an idea of what the elements of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ are, let us attempt to pair off each element of $\mathbb {N}$ with each element of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ to show that these infinite sets are equinumerous.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] In other words, we will attempt to pair off each element of $\mathbb {N}$ with an element from the infinite set ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ , so that no element from either infinite set remains unpaired.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Given such a pairing, some natural numbers are paired with subsets that contain the very same number.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For instance, in our example the number 2 is paired with the subset {1, 2, 3}, which contains 2 as a member.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Other natural numbers are paired with subsets that do not contain them.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] For instance, in our example the number 1 is paired with the subset {4, 5}, which does not contain the number 1.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Using this idea, let us build a special set of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] This set will provide the contradiction we seek.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Let B be the set of *all* non-selfish natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] By definition, the power set ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ contains all sets of natural numbers, and so it contains this set B as an element.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] If the mapping is bijective, B must be paired off with some natural number, say b .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] If b is in B , then b is selfish because it is in the corresponding set, which contradicts the definition of B .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] If b is not in B , then it is non-selfish and it should instead be a member of B .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Therefore, no such element b which maps to B can exist.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Since there is no natural number which can be paired with B , we have contradicted our original supposition, that there is a bijection between $\mathbb {N}$ and ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] This would mean that every natural number x maps to a subset of natural numbers that contains x .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Then, every number maps to a nonempty set and no number maps to the empty set.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] But the empty set is a member of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ , so the mapping still does not cover ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Through this proof by contradiction we have proven that the cardinality of $\mathbb {N}$ and ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ cannot be equal.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] We also know that the cardinality of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ cannot be less than the cardinality of $\mathbb {N}$ because ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ contains all singletons, by definition, and these singletons form a "copy" of $\mathbb {N}$ inside of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Therefore, only one possibility remains, and that is that the cardinality of ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ is strictly greater than the cardinality of $\mathbb {N}$ , proving Cantor's theorem.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Cantor's theorem and its proof are closely related to two paradoxes of set theory.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Cantor's paradox is the name given to a contradiction following from Cantor's theorem together with the assumption that there is a set containing all sets, the universal set V .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] By Cantor's theorem $|{\mathcal {P}}(X)|>|X|$ for any set X .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] On the other hand, all elements of ${\mathcal {P}}(V)$ are sets, and thus contained in V , therefore $|{\mathcal {P}}(V)|\leq |V|$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] This argument is known as Russell's paradox.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] As a point of subtlety, the version of Russell's paradox we have presented here is actually a theorem of Zermelo; we can conclude from the contradiction obtained that we must reject the hypothesis that *R**U*∈*U*, thus disproving the existence of a set containing all sets.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Had we used unrestricted comprehension (as in Frege's system for instance) by defining the Russell set simply as $R=\left\{\,x:x\not \in x\,\right\}$ , then the axiom system itself would have entailed the contradiction, with no further hypotheses needed.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Despite the syntactical similarities between the Russell set (in either variant) and the Cantor diagonal set, Alonzo Church emphasized that Russell's paradox is independent of considerations of cardinality and its underlying notions like one-to-one correspondence.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Cantor gave essentially this proof in a paper published in 1891 "Über eine elementare Frage der Mannigfaltigkeitslehre", where the diagonal argument for the uncountability of the reals also first appears (he had earlier proved the uncountability of the reals by other methods).
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] The version of this argument he gave in that paper was phrased in terms of indicator functions on a set rather than subsets of a set.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] He showed that if *f* is a function defined on *X* whose values are 2-valued functions on *X*, then the 2-valued function *G*(*x*) = 1 − *f*(*x*)(*x*) is not in the range of *f*.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Bertrand Russell has a very similar proof in *Principles of Mathematics* (1903, section 348), where he shows that there are more propositional functions than objects.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] "For suppose a correlation of all objects and some propositional functions to have been affected, and let phi-*x* be the correlate of *x*.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] "phi-*x* does not hold of *x*" is a propositional function not contained in this correlation; for it is true or false of *x* according as phi-*x* is false or true of *x*, and therefore it differs from phi-*x* for every value of *x*." He attributes the idea behind the proof to Cantor.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Ernst Zermelo has a theorem (which he calls "Cantor's Theorem") that is identical to the form above in the paper that became the foundation of modern set theory ("Untersuchungen über die Grundlagen der Mengenlehre I"), published in 1908.
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Lawvere's fixed-point theorem provides for a broad generalization of Cantor's theorem to any category with finite products in the following way: let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be such a category, and let 1 be a terminal object in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Suppose that Y is an object in ${\mathcal {C}}$ and that there exists an endomorphism $\alpha :Y\to Y$ that does not have any fixed points; that is, there is no morphism $y:1\to Y$ that satisfies $\alpha \circ y=y$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] Then there is no object T of ${\mathcal {C}}$ such that a morphism $f:T\times T\to Y$ can parameterize all morphisms $T\to Y$ .
[src:set-theory/cantor-s-theorem] In other words, for every object T and every morphism $f:T\times T\to Y$ , an attempt to write maps $T\to Y$ as maps of the form $f(-,x):T\to Y$ must leave out at least one map $T\to Y$ .
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In mathematics, **cardinality** is an inherent property of sets, roughly meaning the number of individual objects they contain, which may be infinite.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The concept is understood through one-to-one correspondences between sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, if their objects can be paired such that each object has a pair, and no object is paired more than once.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Two sets are said to be ***equinumerous*** or *have the same cardinality* if there exists a one-to-one correspondence between them.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Otherwise, under the axiom of choice, one of the two sets must be equinumerous with a strict subset of the other and is said to be *strictly smaller* than it; the other set is *strictly larger*.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Using this concept, it is possible to show there are different sizes of infinity.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A set is countably infinite if it can be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the set of natural numbers ⁠ $\{1,2,3,4,\cdots \}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the set of even numbers ⁠ $\{2,4,6,\cdots \}$ ⁠ and the set of rational numbers are countable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Uncountable sets are those strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The set of all real numbers and the powerset of the set of natural numbers are proven to be uncountable by so-called diagonal arguments.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theorem generalizes these arguments to show there is an infinite hierarchy of infinities.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For finite sets, cardinality recovers the usual concept of size as "number of elements." However, it is more often difficult to ascribe "sizes" to infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A system of cardinal numbers can be developed to extend the role of natural numbers in answering "how many".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Most commonly, the Aleph numbers ⁠ $\aleph _{0},\aleph _{1},\aleph _{2},...\aleph _{\omega },\aleph _{\omega +1}...$ ⁠ are used, since their definition naturally extends the process of counting, and it can be shown that every infinite set has cardinality equivalent to some Aleph.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The set of natural numbers has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The question of whether the real numbers have cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ is known as the continuum hypothesis, which has been shown to be both unprovable and undisprovable in standard set theories such as Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Alternative set theories and additional axioms give rise to different properties and have often strange or unintuitive consequences.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, every theory of cardinality using standard logical foundations of mathematics admits Skolem's paradox.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The basic concepts of cardinality go back as early as the 6th century BCE, and there are several close encounters with it throughout history, however, the results were generally dismissed as paradoxical.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] It is considered to have been first introduced formally to mathematics by Georg Cantor at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theory of cardinality was then formalized, popularized, and explored by many influential mathematicians of the time, and has since become a fundamental concept of mathematics.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cardinality is an inherent property of sets which defines their size, roughly meaning the number of individual objects they contain.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Fundamentally however, it is different from the concepts of number or counting as the cardinalities of two sets can be compared without referring to their number of elements, or defining number at all.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, in the image above, a set of apples is compared to a set of oranges such that every fruit is used exactly once which shows these two sets have the same cardinality, even if one does not know how many of each there are.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, cardinality is measured by putting sets in so-called one-to-one correspondence: each object in one set can be assigned a dedicated "pair" in the other, and no object from either set left unpaired.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] If it is possible, the sets are said to have the *same cardinality*, and if not, one set is said to be *strictly larger* or *strictly smaller* than the other.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The basic concepts of cardinality are developed in terms of sets and functions, which are more abstract than their counterparts outside of mathematics.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Informally, a set can be understood as any collection of objects, usually represented with curly braces.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, ⁠ $S=\{1,2,3\}$ ⁠ specifies a set, called ⁠ S ⁠, which contains the numbers 1, 2, and 3.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The symbol ⁠ $\in$ ⁠ represents set membership, for example ⁠ $1\in S$ ⁠ says "1 is a member of the set ⁠ S ⁠" which is true by the definition of ⁠ S ⁠ above.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Here ⁠ S ⁠ is finite, but that is not a requirement in general.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The only requirement for a set is that it is well-defined.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, for any object, ⁠ x ⁠, one can determine whether ⁠ x ⁠ belongs to that set ⁠ $(x\in S)$ ⁠, or ⁠ x ⁠ does not belong to that set ⁠ $(x\notin S)$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] One example of an infinite set is the set of all natural numbers ⁠ $\{1,2,3,\cdots \}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A function, or correspondence, maps each member of one set to a unique member of another, often represented with an arrow diagram.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the adjacent table depicts several functions which map sets of natural numbers to sets of letters.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] If a function does not map two members to the same place, it is called injective.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] If a function covers every member in the output set, it is called surjective.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] If a function is both injective and surjective, it is called bijective or a one-to-one correspondence.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Functions are not limited to those one can draw an arrow diagram for, so long as the function is well-defined.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, for each possible input, the output is defined.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The term *cardinality* originates from the post-classical Latin *cardo* ("to hinge"), which referred to something central or pivotal, both literally and metaphorically.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This passed into medieval Latin and then into English, where *cardinal* came to describe things considered to be, in some sense, fundamental, such as, *cardinal sins*, *cardinal directions*, and (in linguistics) *cardinal numbers*.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The last of which referred to numbers used for counting (e.g., *one*, *two*, *three*), as opposed to *ordinal numbers*, which express order (e.g., *first, second, third*), and *nominal numbers* used for labeling without meaning (e.g., jersey numbers and serial numbers).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In mathematics, the notion of cardinality was first introduced by German mathematician Georg Cantor in the late 19th century, who used the term *Mächtigkeit*, which may be translated as "magnitude" or "power", though Cantor credited the term to a work by Jakob Steiner on projective geometry.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Around 1930, the terms *cardinality* and *cardinal number* were adopted from the grammatical sense, and later translations would use these terms.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] An intuitive relationship between two sets having the "same size" is that their objects can be paired one-to-one.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, if each object in one set can be assigned a dedicated "pair" in the other, and no object from either set left unpaired, there are the same number of objects in each set.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A one-to-one pairing between two sets defines a bijective function between them by mapping each object to its pair.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Similarly, a bijection between two sets defines a pairing of their elements by pairing each object with the one it maps to.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Therefore, these notions of "pairing" and "bijection" are, at least intuitively, equivalent.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Two sets are said to have the *same cardinality* or be *equinumerous* if their members can be paired one-to-one.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, if there exists a function between them which is bijective.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This is often written as ⁠ $A\sim B$ ⁠, or ⁠ $A\approx B$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Alternatively, these sets may be said to be *equivalent*, *similar*, *equipotent*, or *equipollent*.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The property for finite sets that "the whole is greater than the part" is no longer true for infinite sets, and the existence of surjections or injections that do not work does not prove that there is no bijection.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the function ⁠ g ⁠ from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ E ⁠, defined by multiplying by 4, ⁠ $g(n)=4n$ ⁠, is injective, but not surjective (since 2, for instance, is not mapped to).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further, the function ⁠ h ⁠ from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ E ⁠, defined by rounding down to the nearest even number, ⁠ $h(n)=2\operatorname {floor} (n/2)$ ⁠ (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] *floor function*), is surjective, but not injective, (since 0 and 1 for instance both map to 0).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Neither ⁠ g ⁠ nor ⁠ h ⁠ can challenge ⁠ $E\sim \mathbb {N}$ ⁠, which was established by the existence of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A fundamental result in developing a theory of cardinality is that equinumerosity forms an equivalence relation—that is, a relation satisfying the same three basic properties as equality: reflexivity, symmetry, and transitivity.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Reflexivity, the property that every set has the same cardinality as itself ⁠ $(A\sim A)$ ⁠, follows from the identity function: for any set ⁠ A ⁠, the function that maps each element to itself is a bijection from ⁠ A ⁠ to **⁠ A ⁠**.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Symmetry, the property that, if ⁠ A ⁠ has the same cardinality as ⁠ B ⁠ ⁠ $(A\sim B)$ ⁠, then ⁠ B ⁠ has the same cardinality as ⁠ A ⁠ ⁠ $(B\sim A)$ ⁠, holds because any bijection ⁠ $f:A\to B$ ⁠ has an inverse function ⁠ $f^{-1}:B\to A$ ⁠, which is also bijective.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since equinumerosity satisfies all three properties, it is an equivalence relation.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This means that it groups sets into equivalence classes—groups of sets that are all equinumerous with one another—where each group defines a possible size of a set.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This motivates the notion of cardinal numbers, which are representatives that stand for the "size" of each group, developed in the section below.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A set ⁠ A ⁠ is not larger than a set ⁠ B ⁠ if it can be mapped into ⁠ B ⁠ without overlap.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, the cardinality of ⁠ A ⁠ is less than or equal to the cardinality of ⁠ B ⁠ if there is an injective function from ⁠ A ⁠ to **⁠ B ⁠**, or equivalently, if there is a surjection from **⁠ B ⁠** to ⁠ A ⁠ (or ⁠ A ⁠ is empty).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, if ⁠ A ⁠ has four elements and ⁠ B ⁠ has five, then the following are true ⁠ $A\preceq A$ ⁠, ⁠ $A\preceq B$ ⁠, and ⁠ $A\prec B$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The basic properties of an inequality are reflexivity (for any ⁠ a ⁠, ⁠ $a\leq a$ ⁠), transitivity (if ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ and ⁠ $b\leq c$ ⁠, then ⁠ $a\leq c$ ⁠) and antisymmetry (if ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ and ⁠ $b\leq a$ ⁠, then ⁠ $a=b$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cardinal inequality ⁠ $(\preceq )$ ⁠ as defined above is reflexive since the identity function is injective, and is transitive by function composition.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Antisymmetry—the fact that, given injections in both directions, then one can find a bijection—is non-trivial, and is the content of the so-called Schröder–Bernstein theorem.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Given injections in both directions (⁠ $f:A\to B$ ⁠, and ⁠ $g:B\to A$ ⁠), take set ⁠ A ⁠ and "color" each point blue.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then take the image of set ⁠ B ⁠ on ⁠ A ⁠ after the injection—that is, the set of points that the injection projects on to—and color those red.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then take the image of ⁠ A ⁠ on this image of ⁠ B ⁠, and color those points blue again.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] By recursively alternating the images of these sets, one obtains a "coloring" of the original set (see illustration).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For each point, it either stops at some finite step—and thus is definitively colored blue or red—or continues switching indefinitely.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Of the points in ⁠ A ⁠ that are definitively colored blue, map them into the next recursive image (i.e. by applying ⁠ f ⁠ then ⁠ g ⁠), leaving all other points in place.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This transforms the set ⁠ A ⁠ into exactly the image of ⁠ B ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Taking this transformation, followed by the inverse of ⁠ g ⁠, gives a bijection from ⁠ A ⁠ to ⁠ B ⁠ (since ⁠ g ⁠ is injective and surjective on its image, its inverse is bijective).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A further property of cardinal inequality is totality, which says that any two sets are comparable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is, for any ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠, either ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ or ⁠ $b\leq a$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A full proof of which requires concepts introduced later, however the argument can be briefly summarized as follows.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Every well-ordered set is isomorphic to a unique ordinal number, called the order type of the set.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] By the well-ordering theorem, every set can be well-ordered.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, by comparing their order types, one can show that ⁠ $A\preceq B$ ⁠ or ⁠ $B\preceq A$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This fact is equivalent to the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A set is called *countable* if it is finite or has a bijection with the set of natural numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, in which case it is called *countably infinite*.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The term *denumerable* is also sometimes used for countably infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the set of all even natural numbers is countable, and therefore has the same cardinality as the whole set of natural numbers, even though it is a proper subset.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Similarly, the set of square numbers is countable, which was considered paradoxical for hundreds of years before modern set theory (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, several other examples have historically been considered surprising or initially unintuitive since the rise of set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] On the left, a version for the positive rational numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The rational numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {Q} )$ ⁠ are those which can be expressed as the quotient or fraction ⁠ ${\tfrac {p}{q}}$ ⁠ of two integers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The rational numbers can be shown to be countable by considering the set of fractions as the set of all ordered pairs of integers, which can be visualized as the set of all integer points on a grid.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, an intuitive function can be described by drawing a line in a repeating pattern, or spiral, which eventually goes through each point in the grid.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, going through each diagonal on the grid for positive fractions, or through a lattice spiral for all integer pairs.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] These over-cover the rationals, since, for example, the fractions ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {2}{4}},\,{\frac {3}{6}},\,{\frac {4}{8}},\,\dots$ ⁠ all get mapped to ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}$ ⁠, as the grid method treats these all as distinct ordered pairs.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] So this function shows ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {Q} \vert \leq \vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠ not ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {Q} \vert =\vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This can be corrected by "skipping over" these numbers in the grid, using the Schröder–Bernstein theorem, or by designing a function which does this naturally, for example using the Calkin–Wilf tree.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A number is called algebraic if it is a solution of some polynomial equation with integer coefficients.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the square root of two ⁠ ${\sqrt {2}}$ ⁠ is a solution to ⁠ $x^{2}-2=0$ ⁠, and the rational number ⁠ $p/q$ ⁠ is the solution to ⁠ $qx-p=0$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Conversely, a number which cannot be the root of any polynomial is called transcendental.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Two examples include Euler's number (*e*) and pi (π).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In general, proving a number is transcendental is considered to be very difficult, and only a few classes of transcendental numbers are known.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, it can be shown that the set of algebraic numbers is countable by ordering the polynomials lexicographically (for example, see *Cantor's first set theory article § The proofs*).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since the set of algebraic numbers is countable while the real numbers are uncountable (shown in the following subsection), the transcendental numbers must form the vast majority of real numbers, even though they are individually much harder to identify.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] That is to say, almost all real numbers are transcendental.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel is a popular thought experiment devised by the German mathematician David Hilbert to illustrate a counterintuitive property of countably infinite sets, allowing them to have the same cardinality as a proper subset of themselves.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The scenario begins by imagining a hotel with an infinite number of rooms, one for each natural number, all of which are occupied.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] But then a new guest walks in asking for a room.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The hotel accommodates by moving the occupant of room 1 to room 2, the occupant of room 2 to room 3, room 3 to room 4, and in general, room n to room n+1.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then every guest still has a room, but room 1 is open for the new guest.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, the scenario continues by imagining an infinitely long bus of new guests seeking a room.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The hotel accommodates by moving the person in room 1 to room 2, room 2 to room 4, and in general, room n to room 2n.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, all the even-numbered rooms are occupied, but all the odd-numbered rooms are vacant, leaving room for the infinite bus of new guests.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The scenario continues further by assuming an infinite number of these infinite buses arrive at the hotel, and showing that the hotel is still able to accommodate.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Finally, an infinite bus which has a seat for every real number arrives, and the hotel is no longer able to accommodate.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A set is called *uncountable* if it is not countable; that is, it is infinite and strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The usual first example of this is the set of real numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠, which can be understood as the set of all numbers on the number line.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] One method of proving that the reals are uncountable is called Cantor's diagonal argument, credited to Cantor for his 1891 proof, though his method differs from the more common presentation.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] It begins by assuming, by contradiction, that there is some one-to-one mapping between the natural numbers and the set of real numbers between 0 and 1 (the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, take the decimal representation of each real number, for example, ⁠ $0.5772...$ ⁠ with a leading zero followed by any sequence of digits.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The number 1 is included in this set since 1 = 0.999...
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Considering these real numbers in a list, it is always possible to create a new number such that the first digit of the new number is different from that of the first number in the list, the second digit is different from the second number in the list, and so on.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The new number must also have a unique decimal representation, that is, it cannot end in repeating nines or repeating zeros.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, if the digit is not 2, make the digit of the new number 2, and if it was 2, make it 3.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, this new number will be different from each of the numbers in the list by at least one digit, and therefore must not be in the list.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This shows that the real numbers cannot be put into a one-to-one correspondence with the naturals, and thus must be strictly larger.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Another classical example of an uncountable set, established using a related reasoning, is the power set of the natural numbers, denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This is the set of all subsets of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, including the empty set and ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ itself.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The method is much closer to Cantor's original diagonal argument.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Again, assume by contradiction that there exists a one-to-one correspondence ⁠ f ⁠ between ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, so that every subset of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is assigned to some natural number.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] These subsets are then placed in a list, in the order defined by ⁠ f ⁠ (see image).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] If ⁠ $1\in f(1)$ ⁠, then ⁠ $1\notin T$ ⁠, that is, if 1 is in the first subset of the list, then 1 is *not* in the subset ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further, if ⁠ $2\notin f(2)$ ⁠, then ⁠ $2\in T$ ⁠, that is if the number 2 is not in the second subset of the list, then 2 *is* in the subset ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then in general, for each natural number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $n\in T$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $n\notin f(n)$ ⁠, meaning ⁠ n ⁠ is put in the subset ⁠ T ⁠ only if the nth subset in the list does not contain the number ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, for each natural number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $T\neq f(n)$ ⁠, meaning, ⁠ T ⁠ is not the nth subset in the list, for any number ⁠ n ⁠, and so it cannot appear anywhere in the list defined by ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since ⁠ f ⁠ was chosen arbitrarily, this shows that every function from ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ to ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ must be missing at least one element, therefore no such bijection can exist, and so ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ must be not be countable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] These two sets, ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠ can be shown to have the same cardinality (by, for example, assigning each subset to a decimal expansion) called the cardinality of the continuum.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cantor's theorem generalizes the second theorem above, showing that every set is strictly smaller than its powerset.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In broad strokes, the proof goes as follows: Given a set ⁠ A ⁠, assume by contradiction that there is a bijection ⁠ f ⁠ from ⁠ A ⁠ to ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, the subset ⁠ $T\subseteq A$ ⁠ given by taking the negation of the "diagonal", formally, ⁠ $T=\{a\in A:a\notin f(a)\}$ ⁠, cannot be in the list.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Therefore, every function is missing at least one element, and so ⁠ $\vert A\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further, since ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ ⁠ is itself a set, the argument can be repeated to show ⁠ $\vert A\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert <\vert {\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(A))\vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Taking ⁠ $A=\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, this shows that ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} ))$ ⁠ is even larger than ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, which was already shown to be uncountable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Repeating this argument shows that there are infinitely many "sizes" of infinity.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In the above sections, "the cardinality of a set" was described relationally.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In other words, one set could be compared to another, intuitively comparing their "size".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cardinal numbers are a means of measuring this "size" more explicitly.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For finite sets, this is simply the natural number found by counting the elements.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This number is called the *cardinal number* of that set, or simply *the cardinality* of that set.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The cardinal number of a set ⁠ A ⁠ is generally denoted by ⁠ $\vert A\vert$ ⁠, with a vertical bar on each side, though it may also be denoted by ⁠ A ⁠, ⁠ $\operatorname {card} (A)$ ⁠, or ⁠ $\#A$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For infinite sets, "cardinal number" is somewhat more difficult to define formally.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, cardinal numbers are not usually thought of in terms of their formal definition, but immaterially in terms of their arithmetic/algebraic properties.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Commonly in mathematics, if a relation satisfies the properties of an equivalence relation, the objects used to materialize this relation are equivalence classes, each of which group objects equivalent to one another.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] These equivalence classes are called the *Frege–Russell* cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, due to John von Neumann, it is more common to assign representatives of these classes.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Given a basic sense of natural numbers, a set is said to have cardinality ⁠ n ⁠ if it can be put in one-to-one correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,\,2,\,\dots ,\,n\}$ ⁠, analogous to counting its elements.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, the set ⁠ $S=\{A,B,C,D\}$ ⁠ has a natural correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,2,3,4\}$ ⁠, and therefore is said to have cardinality 4.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Other terminologies include "Its cardinality is 4" or "Its cardinal number is 4".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In formal contexts, the natural numbers can be understood as some construction of objects satisfying the Peano axioms—a list of properties, such that any system satisfying these properties is, in a certain sense, just like the natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Showing that such a correspondence exists is not always trivial.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Combinatorics is the area of mathematics primarily concerned with counting, both as a means and as an end to obtaining results, and certain properties of finite structures.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The notion cardinality of finite sets is closely tied to many basic combinatorial principles, and provides a set-theoretic foundation to recover them.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] It can be shown by induction on the possible sizes of sets that finite cardinality corresponds uniquely with natural numbers (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] *Finite set § Uniqueness of cardinality*).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This is related to several other concepts, verifying Hume's principle and the basis of bijective proofs, and is equivalent to a certain formulation of the pigeonhole principle, that a finite set cannot be put in one to one correspondence with a proper subset of itself.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The addition principle asserts that given disjoint sets ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠, ⁠ $\vert A\cup B\vert =\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠, intuitively meaning that the sum of the parts is equal to the whole.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The multiplication principle asserts that given two sets ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠, ⁠ $\vert A\times B\vert =\vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠, intuitively meaning that there are ⁠ $\vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠ ways to pair objects from these sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Both of these can be proven by a bijective proof, together with induction.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The more general result is the inclusion–exclusion principle, which defines how to count the number of elements in overlapping sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Naturally, a set is defined to be finite if it is empty or can be put in correspondence with the set ⁠ $\{1,\,2,\,\dots ,\,n\}$ ⁠, for some natural number ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The aleph numbers are a sequence of cardinal numbers that represent the sizes of infinite sets, denoted with an aleph ⁠ $\aleph$ ⁠, the first letter of the Hebrew alphabet.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The first aleph number is ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, called "aleph-nought", "aleph-zero", or "aleph-null", which represents the cardinality of the set of all natural numbers: ⁠ $\aleph _{0}=\vert \mathbb {N} \vert =\vert \{0,1,2,3,\cdots \}\vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ represents the next largest cardinality, then ⁠ $\aleph _{2}$ ⁠, and so on.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The most common way this is formalized in set theory is through Von Neumann ordinals, known as Von Neumann cardinal assignment.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Ordinal numbers generalize the notion of *order* to infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, 2 comes after 1, denoted ⁠ $1<2$ ⁠, and 3 comes after both, denoted ⁠ $1<2<3$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, one defines a new number, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, which comes after every natural number, denoted ⁠ $1<2<3<\cdots <\omega$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further ⁠ $\omega <\omega +1<\dots <\omega +\omega =\omega \cdot 2$ ⁠, and so on.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Defining ⁠ ${\displaystyle \omega$ ⁠ gives ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ the desired property of being the smallest ordinal greater than all finite ordinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since ⁠ $\omega \sim \mathbb {N}$ ⁠ by the natural correspondence, one may define ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ as the set of all finite ordinals.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ is the set of all countable ordinals (all ordinals ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ with cardinality ⁠ $\vert \alpha \vert \leq \aleph _{0}$ ⁠), the first uncountable ordinal.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since a set cannot contain itself, ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠ must have a strictly larger cardinality: ⁠ $\aleph _{0}<\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Furthermore, ⁠ $\aleph _{2}$ ⁠ is the set of all ordinals with cardinality less than or equal to ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠, and in general the successor cardinal ⁠ $\kappa ^{+}$ ⁠is the set of all ordinals with cardinality up to ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Put another way for infinite cardinals, ⁠ $\kappa ^{+}$ ⁠ is the number of possible well-orderings on ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ up to order isomorphism.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Proving that such a set always exists is known as Hartogs' theorem, wherein the smallest ordinal not less or equal to than a set ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ is called the Hartogs number of ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, ⁠ $\aleph _{\lambda }$ ⁠ for a limit ordinal ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is the union of all lesser alephs.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The importance of ordinal numbers here is to generalize the notion of counting to infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] When counting, one implicitly assigns an order to their set of objects, but no matter what order one assigns the final result of the count is always the same, which demonstrates the connection between cardinal and ordinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further, by the well-ordering theorem, there cannot exist any set with cardinality between ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\aleph _{1}$ ⁠, and every infinite set has some cardinality corresponding uniquely to some aleph ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠, for some ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] This allows one to use a constructive definition of the cardinality function, by assigning each set to its equinumerous aleph.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Basic arithmetic can be done on cardinal numbers in a very natural way, by extending the theorems for finite combinatorial principles above.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The intuitive principle that if ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠ are disjoint then addition of these sets is simply taking their union, written as ⁠ $\vert A\cup B\vert =\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus if ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠ are infinite, cardinal addition is defined as ⁠ ${\displaystyle \vert A\vert +\vert B\vert$ ⁠ where ⁠ $\sqcup$ ⁠ denotes disjoint union.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Similarly, the multiplication of two sets is intuitively the number of ways to pair their elements (as in the multiplication principle), therefore cardinal multiplication is defined as ⁠ ${\displaystyle \vert A\vert \cdot \vert B\vert$ ⁠, where ⁠ $\times$ ⁠ denotes the Cartesian product.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Although a lot of properties of finite arithmetic hold for infinite arithmetic, as above and in the table below, strict inequalities (such as Kőnig's theorem) are rare.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, in finite arithmetic, for any nonzero number ⁠ n ⁠, ⁠ $n+n>n$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, since both the set of even numbers ⁠ $(E)$ ⁠ and set of odd numbers ⁠ $(F)$ ⁠ have cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, it shows ⁠ $\vert E\sqcup F\vert =\vert \mathbb {N} \vert$ ⁠ thus ⁠ $\aleph _{0}+\aleph _{0}=\aleph _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In fact, for any infinite cardinal, ⁠ $\kappa +\kappa =\kappa \cdot \kappa =\kappa$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In this way, infinite cardinal addition and multiplication are considered to be remarkably well-behaved (at least under the Axiom of Choice).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Cardinal exponentiation ⁠ $\vert A\vert ^{\vert B\vert }$ ⁠ is defined via set exponentiation, the set of all functions ⁠ $f:B\mapsto A$ ⁠, that is, ⁠ $\vert A\vert ^{\vert B\vert }:=\vert A^{B}\vert$ ⁠ which naturally extends the role of "repeated multiplication" to infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For finite sets this can be shown to coincide with standard natural number exponentiation, but includes as a corollary that zero to the power of zero is one ⁠ $(0^{0}=1)$ ⁠ since there is exactly one function from the empty set to itself: the empty function.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A combinatorial argument can be used to show ⁠ $2^{\vert A\vert }=\vert {\mathcal {P}}(A)\vert$ ⁠, by considering the indicator function of each subset.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In general, cardinal exponentiation is not as well-behaved as addition and multiplication.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, even though it can be proven that the expression ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ ⁠does indeed correspond to some aleph, it is unprovable from standard set theories which aleph it corresponds to.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The *set of all cardinal numbers* refers to a hypothetical set which contains all cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Such a set cannot exist, which has been considered paradoxical, and related to the Burali-Forti paradox.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Using the definition of cardinal numbers as representatives of their cardinalities.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] It begins by assuming there is some set ⁠ $S:=\{X\,\vert X{\text{ is a cardinal number}}\}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Then, if there is some largest cardinal ⁠ $\kappa \in S$ ⁠, then the powerset ⁠ $2^{\kappa }$ ⁠ is strictly greater, and thus not in ⁠ S ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Conversely, if there is no largest element, then the union ⁠ $\bigcup S$ ⁠ contains the elements of all elements of ⁠ S ⁠, and is therefore greater than or equal to each element.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Since there is no largest element in ⁠ S ⁠, for any element ⁠ $x\in S$ ⁠, there is another element ⁠ $y\in S$ ⁠ such that ⁠ $\vert x\vert <\vert y\vert$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\vert y\vert \leq {\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, for any ⁠ $x\in S$ ⁠, ⁠ $\vert x\vert <{\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }$ ⁠, and so ⁠ ${\Bigl \vert }\bigcup S{\Bigr \vert }\notin S$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, the collection of all cardinal numbers is too large to form a set, and is a proper class.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Georg Cantor denoted the collection of all cardinal numbers **ת‎** (tav, the last letter of the Hebrew alphabet), and considered it to be an "inconsistent multiplicity".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The real numbers ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠ formalize the intuitive notion of the *continuum*: the unbroken, gapless set of points on the number line.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] There are numerous ways to construct and analyze the continuum in set theory, for example, sets of Cauchy sequences of rational numbers, or Dedekind cuts.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] However, a somewhat informal definition as the set of infinite sequences of digits, e.g. ⁠ $0.1234...$ ⁠, with the usual arithmetic and order is a popular and sufficient choice for basic arguments involving the continuum.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The cardinality of this set, denoted "⁠ ${\mathfrak {c}}$ ⁠" (a lowercase fraktur script "c"), turns out to be remarkably stable under various transformations.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] For example, all intervals on the real line e.g. ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠, and ⁠ $[0,2]$ ⁠, have the same cardinality as the entire set ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The fact that two intervals of unequal length can be mapped one-to-one has been known, even if considered paradoxical, for thousands of years (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Further, the tangent function is a bijection from the interval ⁠ $\textstyle \left({\frac {-\pi }{2}}\,,{\frac {\pi }{2}}\right)$ ⁠ to the whole real line.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] A more surprising example is the Cantor set, which is defined as follows: take the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠ and remove the middle third ⁠ $\textstyle ({\frac {1}{3}},{\frac {2}{3}})$ ⁠, then remove the middle third of each of the two remaining segments, and continue removing middle thirds (see image).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The Cantor set is the collection of points that survive this process.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The remaining points are exactly those whose decimal expansion can be written in ternary without a 1.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Reinterpreting these decimal expansions as binary (e.g. by replacing the 2s with 1s) gives a bijection between the Cantor set and the interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The Cantor set has a measure or "length" of zero, and yet is still equinumerous to the whole real line.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] In the other direction, into higher dimensions, one can find a bijective map between a one-dimensional line and a two-dimensional square.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Space-filling curves offer a more visual proof, giving a continuous map from the unit interval onto the unit square.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Classical examples include the Peano curve and Hilbert curve.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Although these maps are not bijective, they are indeed sufficient to show ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} ^{2}\vert \leq \vert \mathbb {R} \vert$ ⁠ with the converse being immediate.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Both of these methods can be reused at each dimension to show that ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n}\vert =\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n+1}\vert$ ⁠ and thus ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert =\vert \mathbb {R} ^{n}\vert$ ⁠ for any dimension ⁠ $n\geq 1$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Thus, the real numbers, all finite-dimensional real spaces, and the countable cartesian product have the same cardinality.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] As shown in § Uncountable sets, the set of real numbers is strictly larger than the set of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The Continuum Hypothesis (CH) asserts that the real numbers have the next largest cardinality after the natural numbers, that is ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert =\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] As shown by Gödel and Cohen, the continuum hypothesis is independent of ZFC, a standard axiomatization of set theory; that is, it is impossible to prove the continuum hypothesis or its negation from ZFC—provided that ZFC is consistent, meaning it produces no contradictions.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] The Generalized Continuum Hypothesis (GCH) extends this to all infinite cardinals, stating that ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ ⁠ for every ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Research on CH and GCH continues independent of ZFC, especially in descriptive set theory and through the exploration of large cardinal axioms.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p01] Without GCH, the cardinality of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ cannot be written in terms of specific alephs.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Around the turn of the 20th century, set theory turned to an axiomatic approach to avoid rampant foundational issues related to its naive study (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The most common axiomatic set theory used today is Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] ZFC has been criticized both for being too strong, and too weak.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Similarly, there are many "natural extensions" of ZFC studied by set theorists.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Thus, there exist many alternative systems of axioms each of which has implications to the standard theory of cardinality discussed above.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Choice (AC) is a fundamental principle in the foundations of mathematics which has seen much controversy in its history.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Informally, it states that given any collection of non-empty sets, it is possible to construct a new set by choosing one element from each set, even if the collection is infinite.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The controversy over AC had mostly to do with the nature of how it chose these elements.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Whereas most axioms seem to describe what sets are or allow one to construct explicit sets, AC does not tell you *which* set you have constructed, just that such a choice function exists, leaving the constructed set implicit.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] It is hardly controversial to modern mathematicians.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, because of its unique historical controversy it is often given special treatment not given to other axioms that basic proofs which use it ought to call it out.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Choice is very closely related to the nature of cardinality.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] AC imposes a strict structure on what cardinality can be and what it means to compare to sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Assuming AC is false, cardinality has a much more intricate structure and resists the kind of linear order AC offers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For example, cardinal inequality does not treat injection and surjection equivalently.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Specifically, there exists sets, such that there is a surjection from ⁠ A ⁠ onto ⁠ B ⁠, but no injection from ⁠ B ⁠ into ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Thus injection is a strictly stronger notion, since, given an injection, it is always possible to find a surjection in the opposite direction.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Similarly, although cardinal inequality maintains a partial order, there exist incomparable sets under cardinal inequality, that is, the law of trichotomy fails to hold, and there are sets such that none of ⁠ $A<B$ ⁠, ⁠ $A\sim B$ ⁠, ⁠ $A>B$ ⁠ hold.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Both of these (trichotomy and that surjection implies injection) are equivalent to AC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Because trichotomy does not hold and the aleph sequence has a natural well-order, there exist sets whose cardinality does not correspond to any aleph.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] As such, the cardinality function ⁠ $A\mapsto \vert A\vert$ ⁠ becomes somewhat more difficult to define.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In fact, a cardinality function that maps each set to a unique "representative" of that cardinality—i.e. satisfying Hume's principle, and idempotence (⁠ $\vert \vert S\vert \vert =\vert S\vert$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\vert S\vert \sim S$ ⁠)—is impossible without AC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Set theories without AC address this by adopting the so-called *Frege–Russell–Scott* definition, introduced by Dana Scott, reminiscent of the *Frege–Russell* cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Under this definition, one considers the "Set of all sets" equinumerous with ⁠ A ⁠, but applies Scott's trick to regularize these classes.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Specifically, it reduces this class to only those sets of minimal rank; that is, those sets which appear earliest in the von Neumann hierarchy.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Since the von Neumann hierarchy is well-ordered, there is a least rank, and since these sets all share that rank, their collection is bounded in the hierarchy and thus constitutes a set rather than a proper class.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Cardinal arithmetic is much more involved, losing many of its simplest identities.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The identity ⁠ $\vert A\vert +\vert B\vert =\operatorname {max} (\vert A\vert ,\vert B\vert )$ ⁠ requires a well-defined notion of "max" which requires all sets to be comparable, and therefore does not hold.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Similarly, the statement that ⁠ ${\mathfrak {p}}^{2}={\mathfrak {p}}$ ⁠ for every infinite cardinal ⁠ ${\mathfrak {p}}$ ⁠, and even the statement that the arbitrary product of non-zero cardinal numbers always non-zero—called the *Multiplicative axiom* by Bertrand Russell—are both equivalent to AC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Further, although the Generalized Continuum Hypothesis (GCH, that ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }=\beth _{\alpha }$ ⁠ for every ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠) is independent of ZFC, it can be shown ZF+GCH is sufficient to derive AC, and therefore, if AC is false, it follows that GCH does not hold.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Some set theories include classes, which are collections of sets, which allows theories to discuss any collection of sets without running into issues self-reference (e.g. the set of all sets that do not contain themselves.).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] A class is called a proper class when, at least intuitively, it is "too large" to form a set.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For example, the universe of all sets, the class of all cardinal numbers, and the class of all ordinal numbers are proper classes.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Such set theories include Von Neumann–Bernays–Gödel set theory (NBG), and Morse–Kelley set theory (MK).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Cantor originally called the size of these "too large" sets "absolute infinite", separating it from the transfinite.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The former he characterized by its "inconsistency", causing paradoxes, and associated the concept with God.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Proper classes can, in a sense, be assigned cardinalities.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The first to formally distinguish between sets and classes was John von Neumann, who formalized the notion of "too large to form sets".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] More accurately, he defined a class to be "too big" (a proper class) if and only if it was equinumerous with the whole universe of sets (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] *Axiom of limitation of size*; used as an axiom in MK set theory, and derivable as a theorem in NBG).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Thus, all proper classes have the same "size".
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The axiom has several implications, mostly relating to the limitation of size principles of early set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] It implies the axiom of specification, the axiom of replacement, the axiom of union, and the axiom of global choice.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Large cardinal axioms assert the existence of cardinal numbers which, as the name suggests, are very large—so large that they cannot be proven to exist within ZFC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For example, an inaccessible cardinal is, roughly, a cardinal that cannot be approached from below using basic set-theoretic operations such as unions, limits, and powersets (more formally, a regular, limit cardinal greater than ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Large cardinals are understood in terms of the Von Neumann hierarchy, denoted ⁠ $V_{\alpha }$ ⁠ (for some ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠), which can be understood as the sets that can be obtained from the empty set, followed by recursively applying the powerset ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ times.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] There exist many known properties defining large cardinals, which come seemingly in a linear hierarchy, in terms of consistency strength.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] As an analogy, in ZFC without the Axiom of Infinity can only prove the existence of finite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Therefore ⁠ $V_{\omega }(={\mathcal {P}}(\varnothing )\cup {\mathcal {P}}({\mathcal {P}}(\varnothing ))\cup \cdots )$ ⁠, whose existence is provable in usual ZFC, can serve as a model of ZFC–Infinity, and thus if ZFC is consistent, ZFC–Infinity is consistent.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Analogously, ZFC+"There exists an inaccessible cardinal" implies the consistency of ZFC, since if ⁠ $\kappa$ ⁠ is inaccessible, ⁠ $V_{\kappa }$ ⁠ can serve as a model of ZFC (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Stronger and stronger large cardinal axioms assert the existence of larger and larger cardinals, each of which proves the consistency of the weaker systems.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Large cardinals are at the forefront of set-theoretic research for both practical and philosophical reasons.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In a practical sense, it is often the case that unproven or unprovable conjectures can be settled by sufficiently strong large cardinal axioms.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For example, the existence of a measurable cardinal is inconsistent with Gödel's constructibility axiom.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Similarly, the existence of a Reinhardt cardinal is inconsistent with the axiom of choice, which makes it a much more controversial large cardinal axiom.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In a philosophical sense, according to a platonic view among set-theorists such as W.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Hugh Woodin, these axioms simply extend the system to include sets that are "supposed" to be considered.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] That is, there is some fundamental universe of sets, which these axioms grant further access to.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For this reason, large cardinal axioms are generally given preference compared to other possible axioms of set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This view is controversial among a competing philosophy, sometimes called pluralism, which posits that set theory should be understood as a multiverse of set theories, but no "absolute" or "true" model.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The Axiom of Determinacy (AD) asserts that certain kinds of mathematical games on the natural numbers are determined; that is, one player will always have a guaranteed winning strategy.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The first serious study of the consequences of AD started during the 1960s in descriptive set theory—which, roughly, studies the definable sets of the real numbers—after it was noticed that it leads to very nice regulatory properties of the real numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, it was shown that this axiom is inconsistent with AC and thus was never taken as a fundamental axiom of set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] AD is closely related to the cardinality of the real numbers, giving it a structure different from that under AC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Under AD, the real numbers cannot be well-ordered, meaning ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ does not correspond to any aleph.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Despite this, AD imposes a rigid structure on the real numbers, known as the perfect set property, implying that every set of real numbers is either countable, or has cardinality of exactly ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ ⁠, equal to the whole real line.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Similarly, it also implies that all sets of real numbers are Lebesgue measurable, eliminating the existence of sets whose size is non-zero, but cannot be assigned a length.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Existence of such non-measurable sets allows the Banach–Tarski paradox, demonstrating that one can cut one sphere into finitely many pieces, smoothly rearrange them, and end with two solid spheres, which becomes impossible under AD.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] On the other hand, due to the restrictions on what sets can exist, it implies that one can partition the real numbers into *strictly* more groups than there are real numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Specifically, one can find an injection to show that ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert \leq \vert \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \vert$ ⁠ (equivalence classes of reals, such that ⁠ $x\sim y$ ⁠ iff ⁠ $x-y\in \mathbb {Q}$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, if an injection ⁠ $F:\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \to \mathbb {R}$ ⁠ existed, then there is a linear order on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ (given by ⁠ $a\leq b$ ⁠ if ⁠ $F(a)\leq F(b)$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This allows one to construct a set which cannot be assigned a measure, contradicting AD.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Therefore no such injection could exist, and thus ⁠ $\vert \mathbb {R} \vert <\vert \mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} \vert$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, its relationship with large cardinals and the continuum hypothesis is still of heavy interest among set theorists such as Donald A.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Hugh Woodin, at least in part because AD is equiconsistent with the large cardinal axiom that there exists infinitely many Woodin cardinals.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In model theory, a model corresponds to a specific interpretation of a formal language or theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] It consists of a domain (a set of objects) and an interpretation of the symbols in the language, such that the axioms of the theory are satisfied within this structure.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In first-order logic, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem states that if a countable theory has an infinite model, then it also has models of every other infinite cardinality.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Applied to set theory, it asserts that Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, which proves the existence of uncountable sets such as ⁠ ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ ⁠, nevertheless has a countable model.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Thus, Skolem's paradox was posed as follows: how can it be that there exists a domain of set theory which only contains countably many objects, but is capable of satisfying the statement "there exists a set with uncountably many elements"?
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Skolem's paradox does not only apply to ZFC, but *any* first-order set theory, if it is countable and consistent, has a model which is countable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] A mathematical explanation of the paradox, showing that it is not a true contradiction in mathematics, was first given in 1922 by Thoralf Skolem, who asserted it as a reason against founding mathematics on first order logic.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] He explained that the countability or uncountability of a set is not absolute, but relative to the model in which the cardinality is measured.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This is because, for example, if the set ⁠ X ⁠ is countable in a model of set theory then there is a bijection ⁠ $f:\mathbb {N} \mapsto X$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] But a submodel containing ⁠ X ⁠ which excludes all such functions would thus contain no bijection between ⁠ X ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠, and therefore ⁠ X ⁠ would be uncountable.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In second-order and higher-order logics, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem does not hold.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This is due to the fact that second-order logic quantifies over all subsets of the domain.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Skolem's work was harshly received by Ernst Zermelo, who argued against the limitations of first-order logic and Skolem's notion of "relativity", but the result quickly came to be accepted by the mathematical community.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] From the 6th century BCE, the writings of Greek philosophers, such as Anaximander, discussed infinite sets or objects, however, those objects were generally viewed as paradoxical and imperfect (cf.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This was codified in Euclid's *Elements*, where the fifth common notion stated "The whole is greater than the part", called the *Euclidean principle*.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This principle was the dominating philosophy in mathematics until the 19th century.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Around the 4th century BCE, Jaina mathematics were the first to discuss different sizes of infinity.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] They defined three major classes of number: enumerable (finite numbers), unenumerable (*asamkhyata*, roughly, countably infinite), and infinite (*ananta*, roughly, the continuum).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Then they had five classes of infinite numbers: infinite in one direction, infinite in both directions, infinite in area, infinite everywhere, and infinite perpetually.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] One of the earliest explicit uses of a one-to-one correspondence is recorded in Aristotle's *Mechanics* (c.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] 350 BCE), known as Aristotle's wheel paradox.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The paradox can be briefly described as follows: A wheel is depicted as two concentric circles.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The larger, outer circle is tangent to a horizontal line (e.g. a road that it rolls on), while the smaller, inner circle is rigidly affixed to the larger.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Assuming the larger circle rolls along the line without slipping (or skidding) for one full revolution, the distances moved by both circles are the same: the circumference of the larger circle.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Further, the lines traced by the bottom-most point of each is the same length.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Since the smaller wheel does not skip any points, and no point on the smaller wheel is used more than once, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the two circles.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Galileo Galilei presented what was later coined Galileo's paradox in his book *Two New Sciences* (1638), where he presented a seeming paradox in infinite sequences of numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] It went as follows: for each perfect square ⁠ $(n^{2})$ ⁠ 1, 4, 9, 16, and so on, there is a unique square root ⁠ $\textstyle ({\sqrt {n^{2}}}=n)$ ⁠ 1, 2, 3, 4, and so on.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Therefore, there are as many perfect squares as there are square roots.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, every number is a square root, since it can be squared, but not every number is a perfect square.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Moreover, the proportion of perfect squares as one passes larger values diminishes, and is eventually smaller than any given fraction.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Galileo denied that this was fundamentally contradictory, however he concluded that this meant we could not compare the sizes of infinite sets, missing the opportunity to discover cardinality.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Bernard Bolzano's *Paradoxes of the Infinite* (*Paradoxien des Unendlichen*, 1851) is often considered the first systematic attempt to introduce the concept of sets into mathematical analysis.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In this work, Bolzano defended the notion of actual infinity, presented an early formulation of what would later be recognized as one-to-one correspondence between infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] He discussed examples such as the pairing between the intervals ⁠ $[0,5]$ ⁠ and ⁠ $[0,12]$ ⁠ by the relation ⁠ $5y=12x$ ⁠, and revisited Galileo's paradox.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, he too resisted saying that these sets were, in that sense, the same size.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] While *Paradoxes of the Infinite* anticipated several ideas central to later set theory, the work had little influence on contemporary mathematics, in part due to its posthumous publication and limited circulation.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The concept of cardinality emerged nearly fully formed in the work of Georg Cantor during the 1870s and 1880s, in the context of mathematical analysis.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In a series of papers beginning with *On a Property of the Collection of All Real Algebraic Numbers* (1874), Cantor introduced the idea of comparing the sizes of infinite sets, through the notion of one-to-one correspondence.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] He showed that the set of real numbers was, in this sense, strictly larger than the set of natural numbers using a nested intervals argument.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This result was later refined into the more widely known diagonal argument in 1891, published in *Über eine elementare Frage der Mannigfaltigkeitslehre,* where he also proved the more general result (now called Cantor's Theorem) that the power set of any set is strictly larger than the set itself.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Cantor introduced the notion cardinal numbers together with ordinal numbers, which he viewed as abstractions of sets.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] For a given set ⁠ M ⁠, he wrote ⁠ $\textstyle {\overline {M}}$ ⁠ to mean the abstraction of that set from its elements, while maintaining their order, and cardinal numbers were a double abstraction, written ⁠ $\textstyle M$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] He also introduced the Aleph sequence for infinite cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] These notations appeared in correspondence and were formalized in his later writings, particularly the series *Beiträge zur Begründung der transfiniten Mengenlehre* (1895–1897).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In these works, Cantor developed an arithmetic of cardinal numbers, defining addition, multiplication, and exponentiation of cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This led to the formulation of the Continuum Hypothesis: whether ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Cantor was unable to resolve CH and left it as an open problem.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Parallel to Cantor’s development, Richard Dedekind independently formulated many advanced theorems of set theory, and helped establish set-theoretic foundations of algebra and arithmetic.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Dedekind's *The Nature and Meaning of Numbers* (1888) emphasized structural properties over extensional definitions, and supported the bijective formulation of size and number.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Dedekind was in correspondence with Cantor during the development of set theory; he supplied Cantor with a proof of the countability of the algebraic numbers, and gave feedback and modifications on Cantor's proofs before publishing.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] After Cantor's 1883 proof that all finite-dimensional spaces ⁠ $(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠ have the same cardinality, in 1890, Giuseppe Peano introduced the Peano curve, which was a more visual proof that the unit interval ⁠ $[0,1]$ ⁠ has the same cardinality as the unit square on ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This created a new area of mathematical analysis studying what are now called space-filling curves.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In 1894, attempting to formalize Cantor's "cardinal number", Peano introduced "definition by abstraction": if one can define an equivalence relation, then one may define "that property" which an equivalence class describes.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, this was received harshly by Russell for not considering that this property may not be unique.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] German logician Gottlob Frege attempted to ground the concepts of number and arithmetic in logic using Cantor's theory of cardinality and Hume's principle in *Die Grundlagen der Arithmetik* (1884) and the subsequent *Grundgesetze der Arithmetik* (1893, 1903).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Frege defined cardinal numbers as equivalence classes of sets under equinumerosity.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] However, Frege's approach to set theory was later shown to be flawed.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] His approach was eventually reformalized by Bertrand Russell and Alfred Whitehead in *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913, vol.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This definition of cardinal numbers is now referred to as the *Frege–Russell* definition.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This definition was eventually superseded by the convention established by John von Neumann in 1928 which uses representatives to define cardinal numbers.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] At the Paris conference of the International Congress of Mathematicians in 1900, David Hilbert, one of the most influential mathematicians of the time, gave a speech wherein he presented ten unsolved problems (of a total of 23, later published, now called *Hilbert's problems*).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Of these, he placed "Cantor's problem" (now called the Continuum Hypothesis) as the first on the list.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This list of problems would prove to be very influential in 20th century mathematics, and attracted a lot of attention from other mathematicians toward Cantor's theory of cardinality.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Zermelo's system was extended by Abraham Fraenkel and Thoralf Skolem in the 1920s to create the standard foundation of set theory, called Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC, "C" for the Axiom of Choice).
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] ZFC provided a rigorous foundation through which infinite cardinals could be systematically studied while avoiding the paradoxes of naive set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Ignoring possible foundational issues, during the early 1900s, Felix Hausdorff began studying "exorbitant numbers": roughly, very large cardinal numbers, or what are now called inaccessible cardinals.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] This work was continued and popularized by several other influential set theorists such as Paul Mahlo—who introduced Mahlo cardinals—as well as Wacław Sierpiński, and Alfred Tarski.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Their work would eventually be known collectively as the study of large cardinals.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Inaccessible cardinals were used as Grothendieck universes in category theory as an optional organizational tool to treat certain large categories as sets instead of proper classes.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In 1940, Kurt Gödel showed that the Continuum Hypothesis (CH) cannot be *disproved* from the axioms of ZFC by showing that both CH and AC hold in his constructible universe: an inner model of ZFC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] The existence of a model of ZFC in which additional axioms hold shows that the additional axioms are (relatively) consistent with ZFC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] In 1963, Paul Cohen showed that CH cannot be *proven* from the ZFC axioms, which showed that CH was independent from ZFC.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] To prove his result, Cohen developed the method of forcing, which has become a standard tool in set theory.
[src:set-theory/cardinality-p02] Cohen was awarded the Fields Medal in 1966 for his proof.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In mathematics, specifically set theory, the **continuum hypothesis** (abbreviated **CH**) is a hypothesis about the possible sizes of infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The name of the hypothesis comes from the term *continuum* for the real numbers.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice (ZFC), this is equivalent to the following equation in aleph numbers: $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ , or even shorter with beth numbers: $\beth _{1}=\aleph _{1}$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis was advanced by Georg Cantor in 1878.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] It became one of the most studied problems in set theory, and establishing its truth or falsehood was the first of Hilbert's 23 problems presented in 1900.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The answer to this problem is independent of ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This means the axioms of ZFC can neither prove nor disprove the continuum hypothesis, meaning either the continuum hypothesis or its negation can be added as an axiom to ZFC set theory, with the resulting theory being consistent if and only if ZFC is consistent.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This independence was proved in 1963 by Paul Cohen, complementing earlier work by Kurt Gödel in 1940.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The **generalized continuum hypothesis** states that $\aleph _{\alpha +1}=2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}$ for every ordinal $\alpha$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis was first introduced by Georg Cantor in his 1878 paper "Ein Beitrag zur Mannigfaltigkeitslehre", in a form now called the weak continuum hypothesis which is equivalent to the standard formulation under the then-undeveloped axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor initially presented the weak continuum hypothesis as a theorem, but did not give a proof and later became uncertain of it.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] On 25 October 1882, Cantor wrote to his correspondent Gösta Mittag-Leffler, and formulated the continuum hypothesis (CH) in its modern form and gave his belief he could prove it.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] By the 1890s, many mathematicians in Germany and France were aware of the problem.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor tried for many years to prove CH but never succeeded.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] It became the first on David Hilbert's list of important open questions that was presented at the International Congress of Mathematicians (ICM) in the year 1900 in Paris.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At that point, axiomatic set theory was not yet formulated.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Many erroneous proofs and disproofs of CH were given.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As early as 1884, Paul Tannery claimed to prove CH, but the proof was erroneous.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1890, Beppo Levi claimed to have a proof from assuming that every subset of the real numbers has the Baire property, but no proof was ever published.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At the 1904 ICM in Heidelberg, Gyula Kőnig announced he had disproven CH, drawing wide attention that even reached the Grand Duke of Baden Frederick I via Felix Klein, but a flaw in the proof was found the next day.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Felix Bernstein also published an attempted proof of CH in 1904, but it was wrong and attracted little response.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1926, Hilbert claimed to have solved the continuum hypothesis and gave a proof sketch, but this was also incorrect, although it influenced later ideas in recursion theory.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1906, Kőnig revised part of his attempted CH disproof and established Kőnig's theorem, which by using the concept of cofinality introduced in 1908 by Felix Hausdorff, shows that result that $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ cannot equal $\aleph _{\alpha }$ for $\alpha$ with cofinality $\omega$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hausdorff formulated the question of whether $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ for all ordinals $\alpha$ , which would be named the *generalized continuum hypothesis* by Alfred Tarski in 1925.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1923, Thoralf Skolem conjectured that CH could not be settled by the axioms of Zermelo set theory.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Kurt Gödel proved in 1940 that the negation of the continuum hypothesis, i.e., the existence of a set with intermediate cardinality, could not be proved in standard set theory.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The second half of the independence of the continuum hypothesis – i.e., unprovability of the nonexistence of an intermediate-sized set – was proved in 1963 by Paul Cohen.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Two sets are said to have the same *cardinality* or *cardinal number* if there exists a bijection (a one-to-one correspondence) between them.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Intuitively, for two sets S and T to have the same cardinality means that it is possible to "pair off" elements of S with elements of T in such a fashion that every element of S is paired off with exactly one element of T and vice versa.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hence, the set $\{{\text{banana}},{\text{apple}},{\text{pear}}\}$ has the same cardinality as $\{{\text{yellow}},{\text{red}},{\text{green}}\}$ despite the sets themselves containing different elements.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] With infinite sets such as the set of integers or rational numbers, the existence of a bijection between two sets becomes more difficult to demonstrate.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, this intuitive analysis is flawed since it does not take into account the fact that all three sets are infinite.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Perhaps more importantly, it in fact conflates the concept of "size" of the set $\mathbb {Q}$ with the order or topological structure placed on it.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In fact, it turns out the rational numbers can actually be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the integers, and therefore the set of rational numbers is the same size (*cardinality*) as the set of integers: they are both countable sets.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor gave two proofs that the cardinality of the set of integers is strictly smaller than that of the set of real numbers (see Cantor's first uncountability proof and Cantor's diagonal argument).
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] His proofs, however, give no indication of the extent to which the cardinality of the integers is less than that of the real numbers.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cantor proposed the continuum hypothesis as a possible solution to this question.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In simple terms, the Continuum Hypothesis (CH) states that the set of real numbers has minimal possible cardinality which is greater than the cardinality of the set of integers.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] That is, every infinite set $S\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ of real numbers can either be mapped one-to-one into the integers or the real numbers can be mapped one-to-one into S .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Assuming the axiom of choice, there is a unique smallest cardinal number $\aleph _{1}$ greater than $\aleph _{0}$ , and the continuum hypothesis is in turn equivalent to the equality $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\aleph _{1}$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The independence of the continuum hypothesis (CH) from Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZF) follows from combined work of Kurt Gödel and Paul Cohen.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel showed that CH cannot be disproved from ZF, even if the axiom of choice (AC) is adopted, i.e. from ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel's proof shows that both CH and AC hold in the constructible universe L , an inner model of ZF set theory, assuming only the axioms of ZF.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The existence of an inner model of ZF in which additional axioms hold shows that the additional axioms are (relatively) consistent with ZF, provided ZF itself is consistent.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The latter condition cannot be proved in ZF itself, due to Gödel's incompleteness theorems, but is widely believed to be true and can be proved in stronger set theories.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen showed that CH cannot be proven from the ZFC axioms, completing the overall independence proof.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Essentially, this method begins with a model of ZF in which CH holds and constructs another model which contains more sets than the original in a way that CH does not hold in the new model.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen's independence proof shows that CH is independent of ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Further research has shown that CH is independent of all known *large cardinal axioms* in the context of ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Moreover, it has been shown that the cardinality of the continuum ${\mathfrak {c}}=2^{\aleph _{0}}$ can be any cardinal consistent with Kőnig's theorem.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] A result of Solovay, proved shortly after Cohen's result on the independence of the continuum hypothesis, shows that in any model of ZFC, if $\kappa$ is a cardinal of uncountable cofinality, then there is a forcing extension in which $2^{\aleph _{0}}=\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, per Kőnig's theorem, it is not consistent to assume $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ is $\aleph _{\omega }$ or $\aleph _{\omega _{1}+\omega }$ or any cardinal with cofinality $\omega$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis is closely related to many statements in analysis, point-set topology and measure theory.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As a result of its independence, many substantial conjectures in those fields have subsequently been shown to be independent as well.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The independence from ZFC means that proving or disproving the CH within ZFC is impossible.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, Gödel and Cohen's negative results are not universally accepted as disposing of all interest in the continuum hypothesis.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis remains an active topic of research: see Woodin and Koellner for an overview of the current research status.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis and the axiom of choice were among the first genuinely mathematical statements shown to be independent of ZF set theory.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The latter independence result indeed holds for many theories.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel believed that CH is false, and that his proof that CH is consistent with ZFC only shows that the Zermelo–Fraenkel axioms do not adequately characterize the universe of sets.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Gödel was a Platonist and therefore had no problems with asserting the truth and falsehood of statements independent of their provability.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Cohen, though a formalist, also tended towards rejecting CH.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Historically, mathematicians who favored a "rich" and "large" universe of sets were against CH, while those favoring a "neat" and "controllable" universe favored CH.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Parallel arguments were made for and against the axiom of constructibility, which implies CH.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] More recently, Matthew Foreman has pointed out that ontological maximalism can actually be used to argue in favor of CH, because among models that have the same reals, models with "more" sets of reals have a better chance of satisfying CH.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Another viewpoint is that the conception of set is not specific enough to determine whether CH is true or false.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This viewpoint was advanced as early as 1923 by Skolem, even before Gödel's first incompleteness theorem.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Skolem argued on the basis of what is now known as Skolem's paradox, and it was later supported by the independence of CH from the axioms of ZFC since these axioms are enough to establish the elementary properties of sets and cardinalities.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In order to argue against this viewpoint, it would be sufficient to demonstrate new axioms that are supported by intuition and resolve CH in one direction or another.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Although the axiom of constructibility does resolve CH, it is not generally considered to be intuitively true any more than CH is generally considered to be false.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] At least two other axioms have been proposed that have implications for the continuum hypothesis, although these axioms have not currently found wide acceptance in the mathematical community.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In 1986, Chris Freiling presented an argument against CH by showing that the negation of CH is equivalent to Freiling's axiom of symmetry, a statement derived by arguing from particular intuitions about probabilities.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Freiling believes this axiom is "intuitively clear" but others have disagreed.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] A difficult argument against CH developed by W.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Hugh Woodin has attracted considerable attention since the year 2000.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Foreman does not reject Woodin's argument outright but urges caution.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Woodin proposed a new hypothesis that he labeled the "(*)-axiom", or "Star axiom".
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The Star axiom would imply that $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ is $\aleph _{2}$ , thus falsifying CH.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The Star axiom was bolstered by an independent May 2021 proof showing the Star axiom can be derived from a variation of Martin's maximum.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] However, Woodin stated in the 2010s that he now instead believes CH to be true, based on his belief in his new "ultimate L" conjecture.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Solomon Feferman argued that CH is not a definite mathematical problem.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] He conjectured that CH is not definite according to this notion, and proposed that CH should, therefore, be considered not to have a truth value.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Peter Koellner wrote a critical commentary on Feferman's article.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Joel David Hamkins proposes a multiverse approach to set theory and argues that "the continuum hypothesis is settled on the multiverse view by our extensive knowledge about how it behaves in the multiverse, and, as a result, it can no longer be settled in the manner formerly hoped for".
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] In a related vein, Saharon Shelah wrote that he does "not agree with the pure Platonic view that the interesting problems in set theory can be decided, that we just have to discover the additional axiom.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] My mental picture is that we have many possible set theories, all conforming to ZFC".
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The *generalized continuum hypothesis* (GCH) states that if an infinite set's cardinality lies between that of an infinite set S and that of the power set ${\mathcal {P}}(S)$ of S, then it has the same cardinality as either S or ${\mathcal {P}}(S)$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] That is, for any infinite cardinal $\lambda$ there is no cardinal $\kappa$ such that $\lambda <\kappa <2^{\lambda }$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] (occasionally called *Cantor's aleph hypothesis*).
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The beth numbers provide an alternative notation for this condition: $\aleph _{\alpha }=\beth _{\alpha }$ for every ordinal $\alpha$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] The continuum hypothesis is the special case for the ordinal $\alpha =1$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] GCH was first suggested by Philip Jourdain.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] For the early history of GCH, see Moore.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Like CH, GCH is also independent of ZFC, but Sierpiński proved that ZF + GCH implies the axiom of choice (AC) (and therefore the negation of the axiom of determinacy, AD), so choice and GCH are not independent in ZF; there are no models of ZF in which GCH holds and AC fails.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] To prove this, Sierpiński showed GCH implies that every cardinality n is smaller than some aleph number, and thus can be ordered.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] This is done by showing that n is smaller than $2^{\aleph _{0}+n}$ which is smaller than its own Hartogs number—this uses the equality $2^{\aleph _{0}+n}\,=\,2\cdot \,2^{\aleph _{0}+n}$ ; for the full proof, see Gillman.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Kurt Gödel showed that GCH is a consequence of ZF + V=L (the axiom that every set is constructible relative to the ordinals), and is therefore consistent with ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] As GCH implies CH, Cohen's model in which CH fails is a model in which GCH fails, and thus GCH is not provable from ZFC.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Easton used the method of forcing developed by Cohen to prove Easton's theorem, which shows it is consistent with ZFC for arbitrarily large cardinals $\aleph _{\alpha }$ to fail to satisfy $2^{\aleph _{\alpha }}=\aleph _{\alpha +1}$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Much later, Foreman and Woodin proved that (assuming the consistency of very large cardinals) it is consistent that $2^{\kappa }>\kappa ^{+}$ holds for every infinite cardinal $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Later Woodin extended this by showing the consistency of $2^{\kappa }=\kappa ^{++}$ for every $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Carmi Merimovich showed that, for each *n* ≥ 1, it is consistent with ZFC that for each infinite cardinal κ, 2*κ* is the nth successor of κ (assuming the consistency of some large cardinal axioms).
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] On the other hand, László Patai proved that if γ is an ordinal and for each infinite cardinal κ, 2*κ* is the γth successor of κ, then γ is finite.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] For any infinite sets A and B, if there is an injection from A to B then there is an injection from subsets of A to subsets of B.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Thus for any infinite cardinals A and B, $A<B\to 2^{A}\leq 2^{B}$ .
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] If A and B are finite, the stronger inequality $A<B\to 2^{A}<2^{B}$ holds.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] GCH implies that this strict, stronger inequality holds for infinite cardinals as well as finite cardinals.
[src:set-theory/continuum-hypothesis] Although the generalized continuum hypothesis refers directly only to cardinal exponentiation with 2 as the base, one can deduce from it the values of cardinal exponentiation $\aleph _{\alpha }^{\aleph _{\beta }}$ in all cases.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Sets are of great importance in mathematics; in modern formal treatments, most mathematical objects (numbers, relations, functions, etc.) are defined in terms of sets.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Naive set theory suffices for many purposes, while also serving as a stepping stone towards more formal treatments.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A *naive theory* in the sense of "naive set theory" is a non-formalized theory, that is, a theory that uses natural language to describe sets and operations on sets.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Such theory treats sets as platonic absolute objects.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The words *and*, *or*, *if ... then*, *not*, *for some*, *for every* are treated as in ordinary mathematics.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] As a matter of convenience, use of naive set theory and its formalism prevails even in higher mathematics – including in more formal settings of set theory itself.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The first development of set theory was a naive set theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It was created at the end of the 19th century by Georg Cantor as part of his study of infinite sets and developed as a formal but inconsistent system by Gottlob Frege in his *Grundgesetze der Arithmetik*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Naive set theory may refer to several very distinct notions.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The assumption that any property may be used to form a set, without restriction, leads to paradoxes.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] One common example is Russell's paradox: there is no set consisting of "all sets that do not contain themselves".
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Thus consistent systems of (either naive or formal) set theory must include some limitations on the principles which can be used to form sets.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Some believe that Georg Cantor's set theory was not actually implicated in the set-theoretic paradoxes (see Frápolli 1991).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] One difficulty in determining this with certainty is that Cantor did not provide an axiomatization of his system.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] By 1899, Cantor was aware of some of the paradoxes following from unrestricted interpretation of his theory, for instance Cantor's paradox and the Burali-Forti paradox, and did not believe that they discredited his theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Cantor's paradox can actually be derived from the above (false) assumption—that any property *P*(*x*) may be used to form a set—using for *P*(*x*) "x is a cardinal number".
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Axiomatic set theory was developed in response to these early attempts to understand sets, with the goal of determining precisely what operations were allowed and when.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A naive set theory is not *necessarily* inconsistent, if it correctly specifies the sets allowed to be considered.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] This can be done by the means of definitions, which are implicit axioms.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is possible to state all the axioms explicitly, as in the case of Halmos' *Naive Set Theory*, which is actually an informal presentation of the usual axiomatic Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is "naive" in that the language and notations are those of ordinary informal mathematics, and in that it does not deal with consistency or completeness of the axiom system.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Likewise, an axiomatic set theory is not necessarily consistent: not necessarily free of paradoxes.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It follows from Gödel's incompleteness theorems that a sufficiently complicated first-order logic system (which includes most common axiomatic set theories) cannot be proved consistent from within the theory itself – unless it is actually inconsistent.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] However, the common axiomatic systems are generally believed to be consistent; by their axioms they do exclude *some* paradoxes, like Russell's paradox.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Based on Gödel's theorem, it is just not known – and never can be – if there are *no* paradoxes at all in these theories or in any sufficiently complicated first-order set theory, again, unless such theories are actually inconsistent.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It should be mentioned, however, that results in proof theoretical ordinal analysis are sometimes interpreted as consistency proofs.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The term *naive set theory* is still today also used in some literature to refer to the set theories studied by Frege and Cantor, rather than to the informal counterparts of modern axiomatic set theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The choice between an axiomatic approach and other approaches is largely a matter of convenience.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In everyday mathematics the best choice may be informal use of axiomatic set theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] References to particular axioms typically then occur only when demanded by tradition, e.g. the axiom of choice is often mentioned when used.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Likewise, formal proofs occur only when warranted by exceptional circumstances.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] This informal usage of axiomatic set theory can have (depending on notation) precisely the *appearance* of naive set theory as outlined below.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is considerably easier to read and write (in the formulation of most statements, proofs, and lines of discussion) and is less error-prone than a strictly formal approach.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In naive set theory, a **set** is described as a well-defined collection of objects.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] These objects are called the **elements** or **members** of the set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Objects can be anything: numbers, people, other sets, etc.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For instance, 4 is a member of the set of all even integers.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Clearly, the set of even numbers is infinitely large; there is no requirement that a set be finite.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It does *not* follow from this definition *how* sets can be formed, and what operations on sets again will produce a set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The term "well-defined" in "well-defined collection of objects" cannot, by itself, guarantee the consistency and unambiguity of what exactly constitutes and what does not constitute a set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Attempting to achieve this would be the realm of axiomatic set theory or of axiomatic **class theory**.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For example, Cantor's verbatim definition allows for considerable freedom in what constitutes a set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] On the other hand, it is unlikely that Cantor was particularly interested in sets containing cats and dogs, but rather only in sets containing purely mathematical objects.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] An example of such a class of sets could be the von Neumann universe.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] But even when fixing the class of sets under consideration, it is not always clear which rules for set formation are allowed without introducing paradoxes.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For the purpose of fixing the discussion below, the term "well-defined" should instead be interpreted as an *intention*, with either implicit or explicit rules (axioms or definitions), to rule out inconsistencies.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The purpose is to keep the often deep and difficult issues of consistency away from the, usually simpler, context at hand.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Consistency is henceforth taken for granted unless explicitly mentioned.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] If *x* is a member of a set *A*, then it is also said that *x* **belongs to** *A*, or that *x* is in *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The symbol ∈ is a derivation from the lowercase Greek letter epsilon, "ε", introduced by Giuseppe Peano in 1889 and is the first letter of the word ἐστί (means "is").
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The symbol ∉ is often used to write *x* ∉ *A*, meaning "x is not in A".
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Two sets *A* and *B* are defined to be **equal** when they have precisely the same elements, that is, if every element of *A* is an element of *B* and every element of *B* is an element of *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] (See axiom of extensionality.) Thus a set is completely determined by its elements; the description is immaterial.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For example, the set with elements 2, 3, and 5 is equal to the set of all prime numbers less than 6.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] If the sets *A* and *B* are equal, this is denoted symbolically as *A* = *B* (as usual).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The empty set, denoted as $\varnothing$ and sometimes $\{\}$ , is a set with no members at all.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Because a set is determined completely by its elements, there can be only one empty set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] (See axiom of empty set.) Although the empty set has no members, it can be a member of other sets.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Thus $\varnothing \neq \{\varnothing \}$ , because the former has no members and the latter has one member.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The simplest way to describe a set is to list its elements between curly braces (known as defining a set *extensionally*).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Thus {1, 2} denotes the set whose only elements are 1 and 2.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] This notation can be informally abused by saying something like {dogs} to indicate the set of all dogs, but this example would usually be read by mathematicians as "the set containing the single element *dogs*".
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] An extreme (but correct) example of this notation is {}, which denotes the empty set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The notation {*x* : *P*(*x*)}, or sometimes {*x* |*P*(*x*)}, is used to denote the set containing all objects for which the condition P holds (known as defining a set *intensionally*).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For example, {*x* | *x* ∈ **R**} denotes the set of real numbers, {*x* | *x* has blonde hair} denotes the set of everything with blonde hair.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] This notation is called set-builder notation (or "**set comprehension**", particularly in the context of Functional programming).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Given two sets *A* and *B*, *A* is a **subset** of *B* if every element of *A* is also an element of *B*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In particular, each set *B* is a subset of itself; a subset of *B* that is not equal to *B* is called a **proper subset**.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] If *A* is a subset of *B*, then one can also say that *B* is a **superset** of *A*, that *A* is **contained in** *B*, or that *B* **contains** *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In symbols, *A* ⊆ *B* means that *A* is a subset of *B*, and *B* ⊇ *A* means that *B* is a superset of *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Some authors use the symbols ⊂ and ⊃ for subsets, and others use these symbols only for *proper* subsets.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For clarity, one can explicitly use the symbols ⊊ and ⊋ to indicate non-equality.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] As an illustration, let **R** be the set of real numbers, let **Z** be the set of integers, let *O* be the set of odd integers, and let *P* be the set of current or former U.S.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Then *O* is a subset of **Z**, **Z** is a subset of **R**, and (hence) *O* is a subset of **R**, where in all cases *subset* may even be read as *proper subset*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Not all sets are comparable in this way.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For example, it is not the case either that **R** is a subset of *P* nor that *P* is a subset of **R**.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It follows immediately from the definition of equality of sets above that, given two sets *A* and *B*, *A* = *B* if and only if *A* ⊆ *B* and *B* ⊆ *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In fact this is often given as the definition of equality.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Usually when trying to prove that two sets are equal, one aims to show these two inclusions.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The empty set is a subset of every set (the statement that all elements of the empty set are also members of any set *A* is vacuously true).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The set of all subsets of a given set *A* is called the **power set** of *A* and is denoted by $2^{A}$ or $P(A)$ ; the "P" is sometimes in a script font: ⁠ $\wp (A)$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] If the set *A* has *n* elements, then $P(A)$ will have $2^{n}$ elements.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In certain contexts, one may consider all sets under consideration as being subsets of some given universal set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For instance, when investigating properties of the real numbers **R** (and subsets of **R**), **R** may be taken as the universal set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A true universal set is not included in standard set theory (see **Paradoxes** below), but is included in some non-standard set theories.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In other words, *A*C ("*A-complement*"; sometimes simply *A'*, "*A-prime*" ) is the set of all members of **U** which are not members of *A*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Thus with **R**, **Z** and *O* defined as in the section on subsets, if **Z** is the universal set, then *OC* is the set of even integers, while if **R** is the universal set, then *OC* is the set of all real numbers that are either even integers or not integers at all.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Given two sets *A* and *B*, their **union** is the set consisting of all objects which are elements of *A* or of *B* or of both (see axiom of union).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The **intersection** of *A* and *B* is the set of all objects which are both in *A* and in *B*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Finally, the **relative complement** of *B* relative to *A*, also known as the **set theoretic difference** of *A* and *B*, is the set of all objects that belong to *A* but *not* to *B*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is written as *A* ∖ *B* or *A* − *B*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The set *B* doesn't have to be a subset of *A* for *A* ∖ *B* to make sense; this is the difference between the relative complement and the absolute complement (*A*C = *U* ∖ *A*) from the previous section.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] To illustrate these ideas, let *A* be the set of left-handed people, and let *B* be the set of people with blond hair.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Then *A* ∩ *B* is the set of all left-handed blond-haired people, while *A* ∪ *B* is the set of all people who are left-handed or blond-haired or both.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] *A* ∖ *B*, on the other hand, is the set of all people that are left-handed but not blond-haired, while *B* ∖ *A* is the set of all people who have blond hair but aren't left-handed.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Now let *E* be the set of all human beings, and let *F* be the set of all living things over 1000 years old.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] No living human being is over 1000 years old, so *E* ∩ *F* must be the empty set {}.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For any set *A*, the power set $P(A)$ is a Boolean algebra under the operations of union and intersection.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It follows that, two ordered pairs (*a*,*b*) and (*c*,*d*) are equal if and only if *a* = *c* and *b* = *d*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Alternatively, an ordered pair can be formally thought of as a set {a,b} with a total order.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] (The notation (*a*, *b*) is also used to denote an open interval on the real number line, but the context should make it clear which meaning is intended.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Otherwise, the notation ]*a*, *b*[ may be used to denote the open interval whereas (*a*, *b*) is used for the ordered pair).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] That is, *A* × *B* is the set of all ordered pairs whose first coordinate is an element of *A* and whose second coordinate is an element of *B*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] This definition may be extended to a set *A* × *B* × *C* of ordered triples, and more generally to sets of ordered n-tuples for any positive integer *n*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is even possible to define infinite Cartesian products, but this requires a more recondite definition of the product.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Cartesian products were first developed by René Descartes in the context of analytic geometry.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] If **R** denotes the set of all real numbers, then **R**2 := **R** × **R** represents the Euclidean plane and **R**3 := **R** × **R** × **R** represents three-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] There are some ubiquitous sets for which the notation is almost universal.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] In the list, *a*, *b*, and *c* refer to natural numbers, and *r* and *s* are real numbers.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Integers appear as solutions for *x* in equations like *x* + *a* = *b*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A blackboard bold capital **Z** ( $\mathbb {Z}$ ) often represents this set (from the German *Zahlen*, meaning *numbers*).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Rational numbers appear as solutions to equations like *a* + *bx* = *c*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A blackboard bold capital **Q** ( $\mathbb {Q}$ ) often represents this set (for *quotient*, because R is used for the set of real numbers).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Algebraic numbers appear as solutions to polynomial equations (with integer coefficients) and may involve radicals (including $i={\sqrt {-1\,}}$ ) and certain other irrational numbers.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A **Q** with an overline ( ${\overline {\mathbb {Q} }}$ ) often represents this set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The overline denotes the operation of algebraic closure.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Real numbers represent the "real line" and include all numbers that can be approximated by rationals.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] These numbers may be rational or algebraic but may also be transcendental numbers, which cannot appear as solutions to polynomial equations with rational coefficients.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A blackboard bold capital **R** ( $\mathbb {R}$ ) often represents this set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Complex numbers are sums of a real and an imaginary number: $r+s\,i$ .
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] A blackboard bold capital **C** ( $\mathbb {C}$ ) often represents this set.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Or, more spectacularly (Halmos' phrasing): There is no universe.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] *Proof*: Suppose that it exists and call it U.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Now apply the axiom schema of separation with *X* = *U* and for *P*(*x*) use *x* ∉ *x*.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] where the statement following the implication certainly is false.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It follows, from the definition of Y, using the usual inference rules (and some afterthought when reading the proof in the linked article below) both that *Y* ∈ *Y* → {} ≠ {} and *Y* ∈ *Y* holds, hence {} ≠ {}.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is (perhaps surprisingly) not the possibility of *x* ∈ *x* that is problematic.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] It is again the axiom schema of unrestricted comprehension allowing (*x* ∈ *x*) → {} ≠ {} for *P*(*x*).
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] With the axiom schema of specification instead of unrestricted comprehension, the conclusion *Y* ∈ *Y* does not hold and hence {} ≠ {} is not a logical consequence.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Nonetheless, the possibility of *x* ∈ *x* is often removed explicitly or, e.g. in ZFC, implicitly, by demanding the axiom of regularity to hold.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] or, in other words, no set is an element of itself.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The axiom schema of separation is simply too weak (while unrestricted comprehension is a very strong axiom—too strong for set theory) to develop set theory with its usual operations and constructions outlined above.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] The axiom of regularity is of a restrictive nature as well.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Therefore, one is led to the formulation of other axioms to guarantee the existence of enough sets to form a set theory.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Some of these have been described informally above and many others are possible.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] Not all conceivable axioms can be combined freely into consistent theories.
[src:set-theory/naive-set-theory] For example, the axiom of choice of ZFC is incompatible with the conceivable "every set of reals is Lebesgue measurable".
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In set theory, an **ordinal number**, or **ordinal**, is a generalization of ordinal numerals (first, second, nth, etc.) aimed to extend enumeration to infinite sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Usually Greek letters are used for ordinal number variables to help distinguish them from natural number variables.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A finite set can be enumerated by successively labeling each element with the least natural number that has not been previously used.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This more general definition allows us to define an ordinal number $\omega$ (omega) to be the least element that is greater than every natural number, along with ordinal numbers ⁠ $\omega +1$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega +2$ ⁠, etc., which are even greater than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory asserts that, for *any* set of ordinals, there exists another ordinal greater than all of them.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The answer to the question "What if that set is the set of all ordinals?" (the Burali-Forti paradox) is that the collection of all ordinals is not a set, but a proper class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A linear order such that every non-empty subset has a least element is called a well-order.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The axiom of choice implies that every set can be well-ordered.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Given two well-ordered sets, one is isomorphic to an initial segment of the other, and the isomorphism is unique.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This allows a unique ordinal to be associated with each well-ordered set, known as its order type.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinal numbers are distinct from cardinal numbers, which measure the size of sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Although the distinction between ordinals and cardinals is not this apparent on finite sets (one can go from one to the other just by counting labels), they are very different in the infinite case, where different infinite ordinals can correspond to sets having the same cardinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Like other kinds of numbers, ordinals can be added, multiplied, and exponentiated, although none of these operations are commutative.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinals were introduced by Georg Cantor in 1883 to accommodate infinite sequences and classify derived sets, which he had previously introduced in 1872 while studying the uniqueness of trigonometric series.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A natural number (which, in this context, includes the number 0) can be used for two purposes: to describe the *size* of a set, or to describe the *position* of an element in a sequence.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] When generalized to infinite sets, the notion of size leads to cardinal numbers, and the notion of position leads to the ordinal numbers described here.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In a broader mathematical sense, counting can be viewed as the instantiation of mathematical induction.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] To enumerate a well-ordered set is effectively to verify a property for its elements sequentially.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For the natural numbers, this is standard induction: if a property holds for 0, and its truth for ⁠ n ⁠ implies its truth for ⁠ $n+1$ ⁠, then it holds for all natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This process corresponds to the first infinite ordinal, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Mathematical contexts often require iterating beyond a single infinite limit.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The ordinal ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠ (represented in the figure) exemplifies the concept of **nested induction**.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] It consists of a sequence of distinct copies of the natural numbers ordered one after another.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] To verify a property for all ordinals less than ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠, one performs an "inner" induction (counting through ⁠ $0,1,2,\dots$ ⁠), establishes the limit at ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and then proceeds to the next sequence (⁠ $\omega +1,\omega +2,\dots$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This structure parallels a nested loop in computer programming (e.g., iterating through pairs of natural numbers ⁠ $(j,i)$ ⁠ ordered lexicographically).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinals allow the definition of processes of arbitrary complexity, such as ⁠ $\omega ^{3}$ ⁠ (triple nesting) or ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega }$ ⁠ (induction over the depth of nested induction).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The validity of inductive counting rests on the property of well-foundedness, specifically the requirement that every process can be traced back to a "foundational" element.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A linear order that exhibits this well-foundedness is termed a well-order.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The existence of a "least" or minimal element in every non-empty subset of a well-ordered set grounds the principle of transfinite induction, generalizing standard induction by ensuring that if a property fails to hold, there exists a specific least counterexample.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinals serve as the canonical abstractions of these well-ordered structures.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A fundamental theorem in set theory establishes that any two well-ordered sets are comparable: given two well-orders, either they are isomorphic, or one is isomorphic to a proper initial segment of the other.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This uniqueness implies that well-orders can be classified by their structure alone, independent of specific representations.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Consequently, **ordinal numbers** are defined as the representative forms of these isomorphism classes.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The construction procedure of transfinite sequences implies that the ordinals used to label their elements are well-ordered.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Intuitively, the least ordinal in ⁠ T ⁠ is the "next" ordinal introduced after all ordinals strictly less than every ordinal in ⁠ T ⁠ have been used.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In contrast, ⁠ T ⁠ need not have a greatest element, for example when ⁠ T ⁠ is the set of all natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Being well-ordered is stronger than merely being linearly ordered.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, the real numbers are naturally linearly ordered, but any open interval has no least element.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The importance of well-ordering is that it enables transfinite induction.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If a statement ⁠ $P(\alpha )$ ⁠ about an ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ is not universally true for all ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, i.e., if it has any counterexamples, then it must have a least counterexample.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Conversely, if it can be proven that ⁠ $P(\alpha )$ ⁠ is true whenever ⁠ $P(\beta )$ ⁠ is true for all ⁠ $\beta <\alpha$ ⁠, then it cannot have any least counterexample, and thus it cannot have any counterexample at all, i.e., it is indeed universally true.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In the usual Zermelo–Fraenkel (ZF) formalization of set theory, a well-ordered set is a totally ordered set ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠ such that every non-empty subset ⁠ $T\subseteq S$ ⁠ has a least element.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Here “set” means a collection that is itself an object of ZF, as opposed to a proper class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A well-ordered set can be written as a transfinite sequence by assigning ordinal labels to its elements in a way that respects ordering: ⁠ $a_{\alpha }\leq a_{\beta }$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $\alpha \leq \beta$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] (Such a one-to-one correspondence between two ordered sets is called an order isomorphism.) The labels used in such an enumeration form an initial segment of the ordinals, in the sense that if a label is used then every smaller ordinal label is also used.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] By well-orderedness, there is a unique least ordinal that is not used as a label; this ordinal determines the "length" of the sequence, and is called the order type of the well-ordering.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Thanks to 0-based indexing, the order type coincides with the cardinality for finite sets, including the empty set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] However, for infinite sets, different well-order relations ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ can have different order types.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Order types can be defined without a preexisting notion of ordinals, by working directly with order isomorphisms between general well-ordered sets, just as cardinality can be defined through bijections between general (unordered) sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] As with bijections, being order-isomorphic is an equivalence relation on well-ordered sets; its equivalence classes correspond to order types (ordinals).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In the *Principia Mathematica* approach, the order type of a well-ordered set ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠ is *identified with* its isomorphism class, i.e., the set of all well-ordered sets ⁠ $(S',\leq ')$ ⁠ order-isomorphic to ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Since elements of ⁠ $S'$ ⁠ are allowed to be *anything*, this definition has the “set of all sets” flavor, and in ZF such collections are generally too large to be sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This definition can still be used in type theory and in Quine's axiomatic set theory New Foundations and related systems.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In ZF and related systems of axiomatic set theory, these equivalence classes are generally too large to form sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Consequently, it is necessary to select a unique, canonical representative from each class—a single set that embodies the structure of the well-ordering.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Since the fundamental relation in set theory is set membership (⁠ $\in$ ⁠), the ideal representation is one where the abstract order relation ⁠ < ⁠ is translated directly into the membership relation ⁠ $\in$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The **von Neumann representation** provides this canonical form.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] It relies on the observation that any well-founded relation satisfying certain properties can be mapped to a specific set where the relation becomes set membership.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This mapping is known as the Mostowski collapse lemma.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] When applied to a well-ordering, the Mostowski collapse yields a specific set ⁠ S ⁠ where the order relation ⁠ $x<y$ ⁠ is true if and only if ⁠ $x\in y$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The resulting sets have the property that they are transitive: every element of ⁠ S ⁠ is also a subset of ⁠ S ⁠ (i.e., the union of the set is contained within the set).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In this representation, each ordinal is identified with the set of all preceding ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The first infinite ordinal ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ is represented by the set of all finite ordinals, i.e., the set of von Neumann natural numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {N} =\{0,1,2,\ldots \}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Informally, one may define an ordinal recursively as a downward closed set of ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Such a recursive definition is usually justified with the transitive closure.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The set ⁠ $\omega \equiv \mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is usually defined as the smallest inductive set (containing ⁠ $\emptyset$ ⁠ and closed under successor).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The "smallest" constraint guarantees that each element of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ is either zero or the successor of another element of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, which allows induction to demonstrate that ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ indeed satisfies the formal definition of ordinals stated above.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The non-strict order relation ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ has an alternative characterization: ⁠ $\alpha \leq \beta$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $\alpha \subseteq \beta$ ⁠ for ordinals ⁠ $\alpha ,\beta$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This implies that ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ is a partial order.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] So all ordinal numbers form a well-ordered class ⁠ $\mathrm {ON}$ ⁠, and thus any nonempty set of ordinals equipped with ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ is a well-ordered set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The explicit forms of ⁠ $\mathrm {succ}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\sup$ ⁠ imply that for any set of ordinals, there exists another ordinal greater than all of them.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Every well-ordered set S is order-isomorphic to exactly one ordinal, known as its *order type*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Uniqueness is guaranteed because a well-ordered set cannot be isomorphic to a proper initial segment of itself, preventing isomorphism to two distinct ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The existence of this ordinal is proven by defining a map pairing each $x\in S$ with the ordinal representing the order type of the initial segment ⁠ $S_{x}=\{y\in S\mid y<x\}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] By the Axiom schema of replacement, the range of this map is a set of ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Because this range is downward closed (the order type of a segment of a segment is a smaller ordinal), the range is itself an ordinal $\gamma$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The domain of the isomorphism must be all of S ; otherwise, the least element $z\in S$ outside the domain would imply $S_{z}\cong \gamma$ , which would effectively include z in the domain, a contradiction.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Every ordinal number is one of three types: the ordinal zero, a successor ordinal, or a limit ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] There is variation in the definition of limit ordinals regarding the inclusion of zero.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Some texts, such as *Introduction to Cardinal Arithmetic* by Holz et al., define a limit ordinal as a non-zero ordinal that is not a successor.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In contrast, other standard set theory texts, including Jech's *Set Theory* and Just and Weese's *Discovering Modern Set Theory*, define a limit ordinal simply as any ordinal that is not a successor, which implies that 0 is a limit ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] When the topological definition is used (based on the order topology), 0 is not a limit ordinal because it is not a limit point of the set of smaller ordinals (which is empty); Rosenstein's *Linear Orderings* uses this definition.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] When 0 is included as a limit, ordinals that are strictly greater than 0 and not successors are usually referred to as "nonzero limit ordinals".
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, $\omega$ is a limit ordinal because any natural number is less than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and the successor of any natural number is also a natural number (hence less than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] It is the least limit ordinal because each natural number ⁠ $n\in \omega$ ⁠ is either zero or a successor.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any strictly decreasing sequence of ordinals ⁠ $\alpha _{0}>\alpha _{1}>\alpha _{2}>\cdots$ ⁠ must be finite.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This follows directly from the natural ordering of ordinals being a well-order: if there existed such an infinite decreasing sequence, then the set ⁠ $\{\alpha _{i}\mid i\in \mathbb {N} \}$ ⁠ would be a set of ordinals without a least element.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] By the same argument, a well-ordered set has no infinite strictly descending chains; in fact, assuming the axiom of dependent choice, any total order that satisfies this condition is a well-order, giving an alternative characterization of well-ordered sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This property may be surprising when the initial value is an infinite ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Indeed, for sequences starting from a natural number ⁠ n ⁠, the longest sequence is always one that decreases by 1 every step, leading to a sequence with ⁠ n ⁠ steps (⁠ $n+1$ ⁠ elements).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This strategy of descending to the immediate predecessor remains valid for successor ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] However, a limit ordinal ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ has no immediate predecessor to descend to, so any next term must jump to some ⁠ $\beta <\lambda$ ⁠, skipping infinitely many ordinals strictly between ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, when descending from ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, one must choose a finite natural number, and thus "commit" to the number of maximum remaining steps.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Descending from ⁠ $\omega \cdot k$ ⁠ allows one to make such a commitment ⁠ k ⁠ times, and descending from ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠ allows one to commit to a finite value of ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Larger ordinals may allow more complicated decision structures, but the number of descending steps remains unbounded but finite.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This property is useful for proving termination for any procedure.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If the states of a computation (computer program or game) can be well-ordered—in such a way that each step is followed by a "lower" step—then the computation will terminate.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If $\alpha$ is any ordinal and X is a set, an $\alpha$ -indexed sequence of elements of X is a function from $\alpha$ to X .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This concept, a **transfinite sequence** (if $\alpha$ is infinite) or *ordinal-indexed sequence*, is a generalization of the concept of a sequence.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] An ordinary sequence corresponds to the case $\alpha =\omega$ , while a finite $\alpha$ corresponds to a tuple, a.k.a. string.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] While a sequence indexed by a specific ordinal $\alpha$ is a set, a sequence indexed by the class of all ordinals is a proper class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The Axiom schema of replacement guarantees that any initial segment of such a class-sequence (the restriction of the function to some specific ordinal $\delta$ ) is a set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A sequence is called **normal** if it is both strictly increasing and continuous.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If a sequence *f* is increasing (not necessarily strictly) and continuous and λ is a limit ordinal, then $f(\lambda )=\bigcup _{\beta <\lambda }f(\beta )$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Transfinite induction holds in any well-ordered set, but it is so important in relation to ordinals that it is worth restating here.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any property that passes from the set of ordinals smaller than a given ordinal α to α itself, is true of all ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] That is, if *P*(α) is true whenever *P*(β) is true for all β < α, then *P*(α) is true for *all* α.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Or, more practically: in order to prove a property *P* for all ordinals α, one can assume that it is already known for all smaller β < α.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Transfinite induction can be used not only to prove theorems but also to define functions on ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This is known as *transfinite recursion*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Formally, a function F is defined by transfinite recursion on the ordinals if, for every ordinal α, the value ⁠ $F(\alpha )$ ⁠ is specified using the set of values $\{F(\beta )\mid \beta <\alpha \}$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] *Successor step*: Define $F(\alpha +1)$ assuming $F(\alpha )$ is defined.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] *Limit step*: For a limit ordinal $\lambda$ , define $F(\lambda )$ as the limit of $F(\beta )$ for all $\beta <\lambda$ (either in the sense of ordinal limits or some other notion of limit if the codomain allows it).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The interesting step in the definition is usually the successor step.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If $F(\alpha )$ for limit ordinals $\alpha$ is defined as the limsup of $F(\beta )$ for $\beta <\alpha$ and F takes ordinal values and is non-decreasing, the function F will be continuous as defined above.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinal addition, multiplication and exponentiation are continuous as functions of their second argument.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The existence and uniqueness of such a function are proven by constructing it as the union of partial approximations.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] *Uniqueness and Compatibility:* One proves that any two recursion segments agree on their common domain.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] *Global Definition:* The global class function F is defined as the union of all such unique recursion segments.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For any ordinal α, the value ⁠ $F(\alpha )$ ⁠ is the value assigned to α by any recursion segment defined on a domain larger than α.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The rigorous justification for local existence relies on the axiom schema of replacement for the step of limit ordinals in order to collect the recursion segments into a set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This construction allows definitions such as ordinal addition, multiplication, and exponentiation to be rigorous.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The principle of transfinite recursion also implies that recursion can be performed up to a specific ordinal $\delta$ (defining a set rather than a proper class).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This is often used to define sequences of length $\omega$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, to prove that a normal function f has arbitrarily large fixed points, one constructs a sequence starting with any ordinal $\gamma _{0}$ and defines $\gamma _{n+1}=f(\gamma _{n})$ by recursion on $n<\omega$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Then the limit $\delta =\sup _{n<\omega }\gamma _{n}$ is a fixed point of f because continuity ensures $f(\delta )=f(\sup \gamma _{n})=\sup f(\gamma _{n})=\sup \gamma _{n+1}=\delta$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any well-ordered set is similar (order-isomorphic) to a unique ordinal number $\alpha$ ; in other words, its elements can be indexed in increasing fashion by the ordinals less than ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This applies, in particular, to any set of ordinals: any set of ordinals is naturally indexed by the ordinals less than some ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] So the $\gamma$ -th element in the class (with the convention that the "0-th" is the smallest, the "1-st" is the next smallest, and so on) can be freely spoken of.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Formally, the definition is by transfinite induction: the $\gamma$ -th element of the class is defined (provided it has already been defined for all $\beta <\gamma$ ), as the smallest element greater than the $\beta$ -th element for all ⁠ $\beta <\gamma$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This could be applied, for example, to the class of limit ordinals: the $\gamma$ -th ordinal, which is either a limit or zero is $\omega \cdot \gamma$ (see ordinal arithmetic for the definition of multiplication of ordinals).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Similarly, one can consider *additively indecomposable ordinals* (meaning a nonzero ordinal that is not the sum of two strictly smaller ordinals): the $\gamma$ -th additively indecomposable ordinal is indexed as ⁠ $\omega ^{\gamma }$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The technique of indexing classes of ordinals is often useful in the context of fixed points: for example, the $\gamma$ -th ordinal $\alpha$ such that $\omega ^{\alpha }=\alpha$ is written ⁠ $\varepsilon _{\gamma }$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] There are three usual operations on ordinals: addition, multiplication, and exponentiation.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Each can be defined in essentially two different ways: either by constructing an explicit well-ordered set that represents the operation or by using transfinite recursion.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The Cantor normal form provides a standardized way of writing ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] It uniquely represents each ordinal as a finite sum of ordinal powers of ω.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] However, this cannot form the basis of a universal ordinal notation due to such self-referential representations as ε0 = ωε0.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Ordinals are a subclass of the class of surreal numbers, and the so-called "natural" arithmetical operations for surreal numbers are an alternative way to combine ordinals arithmetically.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] They retain commutativity at the expense of continuity.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Interpreted as *nimbers*, a game-theoretic variant of numbers, ordinals can also be combined via nimber arithmetic operations.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] These operations are commutative but the restriction to natural numbers is generally not the same as ordinary addition of natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Each ordinal associates with one cardinal, its cardinality.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If there is a bijection between two ordinals (e.g. ω = 1 + ω and ω + 1 > ω), then they associate with the same cardinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any well-ordered set having an ordinal as its order-type has the same cardinality as that ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The least ordinal associated with a given cardinal is called the *initial ordinal* of that cardinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Every finite ordinal (natural number) is initial, and no other ordinal associates with its cardinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] But most infinite ordinals are not initial, as many infinite ordinals associate with the same cardinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The axiom of choice is equivalent to the statement that every set can be well-ordered, i.e. that every cardinal has an initial ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In theories with the axiom of choice, the cardinal number of any set has an initial ordinal, and one may employ the Von Neumann cardinal assignment as the cardinal's representation.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] (However, we must then be careful to distinguish between cardinal arithmetic and ordinal arithmetic.) In set theories without the axiom of choice, a cardinal may be represented by the set of sets with that cardinality having minimal rank (see Scott's trick).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] One issue with Scott's trick is that it identifies the cardinal number 0 with ⁠ $\{\emptyset \}$ ⁠, which in some formulations is the ordinal number ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] It may be clearer to apply Von Neumann cardinal assignment to finite cases and to use Scott's trick for sets which are infinite or do not admit well orderings.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Note that cardinal and ordinal arithmetic agree for finite numbers.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The α-th infinite initial ordinal is written ⁠ $\omega _{\alpha }$ ⁠, it is always a limit ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Its cardinality is written ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, the cardinality of ω0 = ω is ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, which is also the cardinality of ω2 or ε0 (all are countable ordinals).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] So ω can be identified with ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, except that the notation $\aleph _{0}$ is used when writing cardinals, and ω when writing ordinals (this is important since, for example, $\aleph _{0}^{2}$ = $\aleph _{0}$ whereas $\omega ^{2}>\omega$ ).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The cofinality of an ordinal $\alpha$ is the smallest ordinal $\delta$ that is the order type of a cofinal subset of ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Notice that a number of authors define cofinality or use it only for limit ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The cofinality of a set of ordinals or any other well-ordered set is the cofinality of the order type of that set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Thus for a limit ordinal, there exists a $\delta$ -indexed strictly increasing sequence with limit ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For example, the cofinality of ω2 is ω, because the sequence ω·*m* (where *m* ranges over the natural numbers) tends to ω2; but, more generally, any countable limit ordinal has cofinality ω.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] An uncountable limit ordinal may have either cofinality ω as does $\omega _{\omega }$ or an uncountable cofinality.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] And the cofinality of any successor ordinal is 1.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The cofinality of any limit ordinal is at least ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] An ordinal that is equal to its cofinality is called regular and it is always an initial ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any limit of regular ordinals is a limit of initial ordinals and thus is also initial even if it is not regular, which it usually is not.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If the axiom of choice holds, then $\omega _{\alpha +1}$ is regular for each *α*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In this case, the ordinals 0, 1, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega _{1}$ ⁠, and $\omega _{2}$ are regular, whereas 2, 3, ⁠ $\omega _{\omega }$ ⁠, and ωω·2 are initial ordinals that are not regular.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The cofinality of any ordinal *α* is a regular ordinal, i.e. the cofinality of the cofinality of *α* is the same as the cofinality of *α*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] So the cofinality operation is idempotent.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The concepts of closed and unbounded sets are typically formulated for subsets of a regular cardinal $\kappa$ that is uncountable.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A subset $C\subseteq \kappa$ is said to be *unbounded* (or cofinal) in $\kappa$ if for every ordinal $\alpha <\kappa$ , there exists some $\beta \in C$ such that $\alpha <\beta$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] To define the property of being closed, one first defines a limit point: a non-zero ordinal $\delta <\kappa$ is a limit point of C if $\sup(C\cap \delta )=\delta$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The set C is *closed* in $\kappa$ if it contains all of its limit points below $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A set that is both closed and unbounded is commonly referred to as a *club set*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Examples of club sets are fundamental to set theory.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The set of all limit ordinals less than $\kappa$ is a club set, as there is always a limit ordinal greater than any given ordinal below $\kappa$ , and a limit of limit ordinals is itself a limit ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If $\kappa$ is a limit cardinal, the set of all cardinals below $\kappa$ is unbounded, and its set of limit points—the limit cardinals—forms a closed unbounded set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Furthermore, if $\kappa$ is a strong limit cardinal (such as an inaccessible cardinal), the set of strong limit cardinals below $\kappa$ is also a club set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Another significant example arises from normal functions (functions $f:\kappa \to \kappa$ that are strictly increasing and continuous); the range of any normal function is a closed unbounded subset of $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Club sets possess structural properties that allow them to generate a filter.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Because $\kappa$ is regular and uncountable, the intersection of any two club sets is also a club set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] More generally, the intersection of fewer than $\kappa$ club sets is a club set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Consequently, the collection of all subsets of $\kappa$ that contain a club set forms a $\kappa$ -complete non-principal filter, known as the *closed unbounded filter* (or club filter).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A subset $S\subseteq \kappa$ is termed *stationary* if it has a non-empty intersection with every closed unbounded set in $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Intuitively, stationary sets are "large" enough that they cannot be avoided by any club set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Using the notation of filters, a set is stationary if and only if it does not belong to the dual ideal of the club filter (the ideal of non-stationary sets).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] While every club set is stationary, not every stationary set is a club; for instance, a stationary set S may fail to be closed.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Furthermore, while the intersection of a stationary set and a club set is stationary, the intersection of two stationary sets may be empty.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The distinction between club sets and stationary sets is central to the definitions of certain large cardinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If $\kappa$ is the smallest inaccessible cardinal, the set of singular strong limit cardinals below $\kappa$ forms a closed unbounded set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Because this club set contains no regular cardinals, the set of regular cardinals below the first inaccessible is not stationary.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This remains true if $\kappa$ is the n -th inaccessible cardinal for some $n<\kappa$ ; the regular cardinals below it will not form a stationary set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A cardinal $\kappa$ is defined as a Mahlo cardinal precisely when the set of regular cardinals below it is stationary.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] By relaxing the condition on the limit cardinals, one defines a cardinal as *weakly Mahlo* if it is weakly inaccessible and the set of regular cardinals below it is stationary.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The closed unbounded filter is not an ultrafilter under the standard Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the Axiom of Choice (ZFC).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This is because one can find two disjoint stationary sets, which precludes the filter from deciding membership for every subset.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For any regular cardinal $\kappa >\omega _{1}$ , the set of ordinals with cofinality $\omega$ and the set of ordinals with cofinality $\omega _{1}$ are disjoint stationary subsets of $\kappa$ .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In the specific case of $\kappa =\omega _{1}$ , the non-existence of an ultrafilter relies on the Axiom of Choice.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Under ZFC, the set of limit ordinals in $\omega _{1}$ can be partitioned into $\omega _{1}$ disjoint stationary sets (a result related to Fodor's lemma).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] However, in models of set theory without the Axiom of Choice, such as those satisfying the Axiom of determinacy, the club filter on $\omega _{1}$ can be an ultrafilter, a property connected to $\omega _{1}$ being a measurable cardinal in those contexts.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] These definitions generalize to proper classes of ordinals.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A class C of ordinals is unbounded if it contains arbitrarily large ordinals, and closed if the limit of any sequence of ordinals in C is also in C .
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This topological definition is equivalent to assuming the indexing class-function of C is continuous.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Notable examples of closed unbounded classes include the class of all infinite cardinals, the class of limit cardinals, and the class of fixed points of the $\aleph$ -function.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In contrast, the class of regular cardinals is unbounded but not closed.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] A class is stationary if it intersects every closed unbounded class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] As mentioned above (see Cantor normal form), the ordinal ε0 is the smallest satisfying the equation ⁠ $\omega ^{\alpha }=\alpha$ ⁠, so it is the limit of the sequence 0, 1, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega }$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega ^{\omega }}$ ⁠, etc.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] One could try to do this systematically, but no matter what system is used to define and construct ordinals, there is always an ordinal that lies just above all the ordinals constructed by the system.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Considerably large ordinals can be defined below ⁠ $\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }$ ⁠, however, which measure the proof-theoretic strength of certain formal systems (for example, $\varepsilon _{0}$ measures the strength of Peano arithmetic).
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Large countable ordinals such as countable admissible ordinals can also be defined above the Church-Kleene ordinal, which are of interest in various parts of logic.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Any ordinal number can be made into a topological space by endowing it with the order topology.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] This topology is discrete if and only if it is less than or equal to ω.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In contrast, a subset of ω + 1 is open in the order topology if and only if either it is cofinite or it does not contain ω as an element.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] See the Topology and ordinals section of the "Order topology" article.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The transfinite ordinal numbers, which first appeared in 1883, originated in Cantor's work with derived sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If *P* is a set of real numbers, the derived set *P′* is the set of limit points of *P*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In 1872, Cantor generated the sets *P*(*n*) by applying the derived set operation *n* times to *P*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In 1880, he pointed out that these sets form the sequence *P'*⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(*n*) ⊇ *P*(*n* + 1) ⊇ ···, and he continued the derivation process by defining *P*(∞) as the intersection of these sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Then he iterated the derived set operation and intersections to extend his sequence of sets into the infinite: *P*(∞) ⊇ *P*(∞ + 1) ⊇ *P*(∞ + 2) ⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(2∞) ⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(∞2) ⊇ ···.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The superscripts containing ∞ are just indices defined by the derivation process.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Conversely, if *P′* is countable, then there is an index *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Hence, they are discrete sets, so they are countable.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Proof of first theorem: If *P*(*α*) = ∅ for some index *α*, then *P′* is the countable union of countable sets.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The second theorem requires proving the existence of an *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] To prove this, Cantor considered the set of all *α* having countably many predecessors.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] To define this set, he defined the transfinite ordinal numbers and transformed the infinite indices into ordinals by replacing ∞ with *ω*, the first transfinite ordinal number.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Cantor called the set of finite ordinals the first **number class**.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The second number class is the set of ordinals whose predecessors form a countably infinite set.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The set of all *α* having countably many predecessors—that is, the set of countable ordinals—is the union of these two number classes.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Cantor proved that the cardinality of the second number class is the first uncountable cardinality.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Cantor's second theorem becomes: If *P′* is countable, then there is a countable ordinal *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Let *P′* be countable, and assume there is no such α.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] In both cases, *P′* is uncountable, which contradicts *P′* being countable.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Therefore, there is a countable ordinal *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Cantor's work with derived sets and ordinal numbers led to the Cantor-Bendixson theorem.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Using successors, limits, and cardinality, Cantor generated an unbounded sequence of ordinal numbers and number classes.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The (*α* + 1)-th number class is the set of ordinals whose predecessors form a set of the same cardinality as the *α*-th number class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] The cardinality of the (*α* + 1)-th number class is the cardinality immediately following that of the *α*-th number class.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] For a limit ordinal *α*, the *α*-th number class is the union of the *β*-th number classes for *β* < *α*.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Its cardinality is the limit of the cardinalities of these number classes.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If *n* is finite, the *n*-th number class has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{n-1}$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] If *α* ≥ *ω*, the *α*-th number class has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Therefore, the cardinalities of the number classes correspond one-to-one with the aleph numbers.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Also, the *α*-th number class consists of ordinals different from those in the preceding number classes if and only if *α* is a non-limit ordinal.
[src:set-theory/ordinal-number] Therefore, the non-limit number classes partition the ordinals into pairwise disjoint sets.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The modern study of set theory was initiated by the German mathematicians Richard Dedekind and Georg Cantor in the 1870s.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In particular, Georg Cantor is commonly considered the founder of set theory.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The non-formalized systems investigated during this early stage go under the name of *naive set theory*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] After the discovery of paradoxes within naive set theory (e.g.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Russell's paradox, Cantor's paradox, and the Burali-Forti paradox, et al.), various axiomatic systems were proposed in the early twentieth century, of which Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (with or without the axiom of choice) is still the best-known and most studied.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Set theory is commonly employed as a foundational system for the whole of mathematics, particularly in the form of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Besides its foundational role, set theory also provides the framework to develop a mathematical theory of infinity, and has various applications in computer science (such as in the theory of relational algebra), philosophy, formal semantics, and evolutionary dynamics.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Its foundational appeal, together with its paradoxes, and its implications for the concept of infinity and its multiple applications have made set theory an area of major interest for logicians and philosophers of mathematics.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Contemporary research into set theory covers a vast array of topics, ranging from the structure of the real number line to the study of the consistency of large cardinals.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The basic notion of grouping objects has existed since at least the emergence of numbers, and the notion of treating sets as their own objects has existed since at least the Tree of Porphyry in 3rd-century CE.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The simplicity and ubiquity of sets makes it hard to determine the origin of sets as now used in mathematics; however, Bernard Bolzano's *Paradoxes of the Infinite* (*Paradoxien des Unendlichen*, 1851) is generally considered the first rigorous introduction of sets to mathematics.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In his work, he (among other things) expanded on Galileo's paradox, and introduced one-to-one correspondence of infinite sets, for example between the intervals $[0,5]$ and $[0,12]$ by the relation $5y=12x$ .
[src:set-theory/set-theory] However, he resisted saying these sets were equinumerous, and his work is generally considered to have been uninfluential in mathematics of his time.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Before mathematical set theory, basic concepts of infinity were considered to be in the domain of philosophy (see: *Infinity (philosophy)* and *Infinity § History*).
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Since the 5th century BC, beginning with Greek philosopher Zeno of Elea in the West (and early Indian mathematicians in the East), mathematicians had struggled with the concept of infinity.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] With the development of calculus in the late 17th century, philosophers began to generally distinguish between potential and actual infinity, wherein mathematics was only considered in the latter.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Development of mathematical set theory was motivated by several mathematicians.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Bernhard Riemann's lecture *On the Hypotheses which lie at the Foundations of Geometry* (1854) proposed new ideas about topology.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] His lectures also introduced the concept of basing mathematics in terms of sets or manifolds in the sense of a class (which he called *Mannigfaltigkeit*) now called point-set topology.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The lecture was published by Richard Dedekind in 1868, along with Riemann's paper on trigonometric series (which presented the Riemann integral).
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The latter was the starting point for a movement in real analysis of the study of “seriously” discontinuous functions.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] A young Georg Cantor entered into this area, which led him to the study of point-sets.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Around 1871, influenced by Riemann, Dedekind began working with sets in his publications, which dealt very clearly and precisely with equivalence relations, partitions of sets, and homomorphisms.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Thus, many of the usual set-theoretic procedures of twentieth-century mathematics go back to his work.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] However, he did not publish a formal explanation of his set theory until 1888.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Set theory, as understood by modern mathematicians, is generally considered to be founded by a single paper in 1874 by Georg Cantor titled *On a Property of the Collection of All Real Algebraic Numbers*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In his paper, he developed the notion of cardinality, comparing the sizes of two sets by setting them in one-to-one correspondence.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] His "revolutionary discovery" was that the set of all real numbers is uncountable, that is, one cannot put all real numbers in a list.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] This theorem is proved using Cantor's first uncountability proof, which differs from the more familiar proof using his diagonal argument.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Cantor introduced fundamental constructions in set theory, such as the power set of a set *A*, which is the set of all possible subsets of *A*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] He later proved that the size of the power set of *A* is strictly larger than the size of *A*, even when *A* is an infinite set; this result soon became known as Cantor's theorem.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Cantor developed a theory of transfinite numbers, called cardinals and ordinals, which extended the arithmetic of the natural numbers.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] His notation for the cardinal numbers was the Hebrew letter $\aleph$ (ℵ, aleph) with a natural number subscript; for the ordinals he employed the Greek letter $\omega$ (ω, omega).
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Set theory was beginning to become an essential ingredient of the new “modern” approach to mathematics.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Originally, Cantor's theory of transfinite numbers was regarded as counter-intuitive – even shocking.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] This caused it to encounter resistance from mathematical contemporaries such as Leopold Kronecker and Henri Poincaré and later from Hermann Weyl and L.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Brouwer, while Ludwig Wittgenstein raised philosophical objections (see: *Controversy over Cantor's theory*).
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Despite the controversy, Cantor's set theory gained remarkable ground around the turn of the 20th century with the work of several notable mathematicians and philosophers.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Richard Dedekind, around the same time, began working with sets in his publications, and was famously constructing the real numbers in 1872 using Dedekind cuts.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Cantor and Dedekind were in correspondence about set theory, especially in the 1870s.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] However, Dedekind's algebraic style only began to find followers in the 1890s.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Cantor also worked with Giuseppe Peano in developing the Peano axioms, which formalized natural-number arithmetic, using set-theoretic ideas, which also introduced the epsilon symbol for set membership.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Possibly most prominently, Gottlob Frege began to develop his *Foundations of Arithmetic*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In his work, Frege tries to ground all mathematics in terms of logical axioms using Cantor's cardinality.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] For example, the sentence "the number of horses in the barn is four" means that four objects fall under the concept *horse in the barn*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Frege attempted to explain our grasp of numbers through cardinality ('the number of...', or $Nx:Fx$ ), relying on Hume's principle.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] However, Frege's work was short-lived, as it was found by Bertrand Russell that his axioms lead to a contradiction.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Specifically, Frege's Basic Law V (now known as the axiom schema of unrestricted comprehension).
[src:set-theory/set-theory] According to Basic Law V, for any sufficiently well-defined property, there is the set of all and only the objects that have that property.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] This came around a time of several paradoxes or counter-intuitive results.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] For example, that the parallel postulate cannot be proved, the existence of mathematical objects that cannot be computed or explicitly described, and the existence of theorems of arithmetic that cannot be proved with Peano arithmetic.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The result was a foundational crisis of mathematics.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Set theory begins with a fundamental binary relation between an object o and a set A.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] If o is a *member* (or *element*) of A, the notation *o* ∈ *A* is used.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] A set is described by listing elements separated by commas, or by a characterizing property of its elements, within braces { }.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Since sets are objects, the membership relation can relate sets as well, i.e., sets themselves can be members of other sets.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] A derived binary relation between two sets is the subset relation, also called *set inclusion*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] If all the members of set A are also members of set B, then A is a *subset* of B, denoted *A* ⊆ *B*.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] As implied by this definition, a set is a subset of itself.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] We call A a *proper subset* of B if and only if A is a subset of B, but A is not equal to B.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Also, 1, 2, and 3 are members (elements) of the set {1, 2, 3}, but are not subsets of it; and in turn, the subsets, such as {1}, are not members of the set {1, 2, 3}.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] More complicated relations can exist; for example, the set {1} is both a member and a proper subset of the set {1, {1}}.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Just as arithmetic features binary operations on numbers, set theory features binary operations on sets.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Some basic sets of central importance are the set of natural numbers, the set of real numbers and the empty set – the unique set containing no elements.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The empty set is also occasionally called the *null set*, though this name is ambiguous and can lead to several interpretations.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The empty set can be denoted with empty braces " $\{\}$ " or the symbol " $\varnothing$ " or " $\emptyset$ ".
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The power set of a set A, denoted ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ , is the set whose members are all of the possible subsets of A.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Notably, ${\mathcal {P}}(A)$ contains both A and the empty set.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] A set is pure if all of its members are sets, all members of its members are sets, and so on.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] For example, the set containing only the empty set is a nonempty pure set.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In modern set theory, it is common to restrict attention to the *von Neumann universe* of pure sets, and many systems of axiomatic set theory are designed to axiomatize the pure sets only.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] There are many technical advantages to this restriction, and little generality is lost, because essentially all mathematical concepts can be modeled by pure sets.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Sets in the von Neumann universe are organized into a cumulative hierarchy, based on how deeply their members, members of members, etc. are nested.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Each set in this hierarchy is assigned (by transfinite recursion) an ordinal number $\alpha$ , known as its *rank.* The rank of a pure set X is defined to be the least ordinal that is strictly greater than the rank of any of its elements.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] For example, the empty set is assigned rank 0, while the set containing only the empty set is assigned rank 1.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] For each ordinal $\alpha$ , the set $V_{\alpha }$ is defined to consist of all pure sets with rank less than $\alpha$ .
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The entire von Neumann universe is denoted V .
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Elementary set theory can be studied informally and intuitively, and so can be taught in primary schools using Venn diagrams.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The intuitive approach tacitly assumes that a set may be formed from the class of all objects satisfying any particular defining condition.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] This assumption gives rise to paradoxes, the simplest and best known of which are Russell's paradox and the Burali-Forti paradox.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] **Axiomatic set theory** was originally devised to rid set theory of such paradoxes.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The most widely studied systems of axiomatic set theory imply that all sets form a cumulative hierarchy.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The above systems can be modified to allow *urelements*, objects that can be members of sets but that are not themselves sets and do not have any members.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] Zermelo set theory was originally defined over a domain consisting of both sets and urelements.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] The *New Foundations* systems of **NFU** (allowing urelements) and **NF** (lacking them), associate with Willard Van Orman Quine, are not based on a cumulative hierarchy.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] NF and NFU include a "set of everything", relative to which every set has a complement.
[src:set-theory/set-theory] In these systems urelements matter, because NF, but not NFU, produces sets for which the axiom of choice does not hold.
